1
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:06,000
25.000 English

2
00:00:26,080 --> 00:00:30,720
Some Like It Hot (1959)

3
00:04:11,760 --> 00:04:13,760
All right, Charlie.

4
00:04:13,840 --> 00:04:17,760
- That the joint? Who runs it?
- I already told you.

5
00:04:17,960 --> 00:04:20,040
- Refresh my memory.
- Spats Colombo.

6
00:04:20,160 --> 00:04:23,360
- What's the password?
- "I've come to Grandma's funeral."

7
00:04:23,440 --> 00:04:25,560
- Your admission card.
- Thanks, Charlie.

8
00:04:25,640 --> 00:04:29,040
If you want a ringside table,
just say you're a pallbearer.

9
00:04:29,160 --> 00:04:31,160
We're all set. Whens the kickoff?

10
00:04:31,240 --> 00:04:34,240
I'd better blow.
If Colombo sees me, it's goodbye, Charlie.

11
00:04:34,360 --> 00:04:36,360
Goodbye, Charlie.

12
00:04:37,760 --> 00:04:40,640
Give me five minutes,
then hit 'em with everything you got.

13
00:04:40,760 --> 00:04:42,800
You betcha.

14
00:04:57,200 --> 00:04:58,600
Good evening, sir.

15
00:04:58,800 --> 00:05:02,280
- I'm Mr Mozarella. What can I do for you?
- I've come to the old lady's funeral.

16
00:05:02,400 --> 00:05:04,680
I haven't seen you at our services before.

17
00:05:04,800 --> 00:05:07,000
- No, I've been on the wagon.
- Please.

18
00:05:07,080 --> 00:05:09,600
Where is the wake?
I'm one of the pallbearers.

19
00:05:09,680 --> 00:05:12,600
Show the gentleman into the chapel.
Pew number three.

20
00:05:12,680 --> 00:05:15,000
Yes, Mr Mozarella. This way, sir.

21
00:05:32,400 --> 00:05:34,880
Well, if you gotta go,
that's the way to do it.

22
00:05:35,080 --> 00:05:37,200
Follow me, please.

23
00:05:49,080 --> 00:05:51,000
- What'll it be, sir?
- Booze.

24
00:05:51,080 --> 00:05:53,280
- Sorry. We only serve coffee.
- Coffee?

25
00:05:53,400 --> 00:05:56,200
Scotch coffee, Canadian coffee,
sour mash coffee...

26
00:05:56,280 --> 00:05:59,000
Scotch. Make it a demitasse,
with soda on the side.

27
00:05:59,080 --> 00:06:02,680
Wait a minute. Haven't you got
a pew not so close to the band?

28
00:06:02,800 --> 00:06:04,600
How about that one over there?

29
00:06:04,800 --> 00:06:08,600
Sorry, but that's reserved
for members of the immediate family.

30
00:06:17,880 --> 00:06:19,680
Oops.

31
00:06:25,280 --> 00:06:28,200
Hey, I want another cup of coffee.

32
00:06:28,280 --> 00:06:30,880
I want another cup of coffee.

33
00:06:41,280 --> 00:06:43,680
Better bring a check
in case the joint is raided.

34
00:06:43,800 --> 00:06:47,880
- Who's gonna raid a funeral?
- Some people don't respect the dead.

35
00:07:10,480 --> 00:07:12,880
Say, Joe. Tonight's the night, isn't it?

36
00:07:13,080 --> 00:07:16,400
- I'll say.
- No, tonight we get paid.

37
00:07:16,480 --> 00:07:20,000
- Why?
- I've got to see a dentist tomorrow.

38
00:07:20,080 --> 00:07:23,000
You wanna blow
your first week's pay on your teeth?

39
00:07:23,080 --> 00:07:26,800
Just a filling. Doesn't have to be gold.

40
00:07:26,880 --> 00:07:31,080
How can you be so selfish? We owe rent.
We owe $89 to Moe's Delicatessen.

41
00:07:31,280 --> 00:07:35,400
The Chinese laundry is suing us.
We owe money to every girl in the line.

42
00:07:35,480 --> 00:07:39,400
You're right. Tomorrow we'll pay
everyone something on account.

43
00:07:39,480 --> 00:07:44,480
No. Tomorrow we go to the dog track
and bet it all on Greased Lightning.

44
00:07:44,600 --> 00:07:47,200
- You'd bet my money on a dog?
- He's a shoo-in.

45
00:07:47,400 --> 00:07:50,440
Max the waiter knows the electrician
that wires the rabbit.

46
00:07:50,480 --> 00:07:54,120
- What are you givin' me with a rabbit?
- The odds are 10 to 1.

47
00:07:54,320 --> 00:07:57,840
- Suppose he loses.
- Why worry? This job'll last a long time.

48
00:07:57,920 --> 00:08:01,840
- Suppose it doesn't.
- Jerry boy, why paint everyzhing black?

49
00:08:01,920 --> 00:08:06,320
Suppose you got hit by a truck.
Suppose the stock market crashes.

50
00:08:06,440 --> 00:08:09,240
Suppose Mary Pickford
divorces Douglas Fairbanks.

51
00:08:09,320 --> 00:08:12,120
Suppose the Dodgers leave Brooklyn.

52
00:08:12,320 --> 00:08:14,240
Suppose Lake Michigan overflows.

53
00:08:14,320 --> 00:08:17,920
Well, don't look now,
but the whole town is underwater.

54
00:08:30,320 --> 00:08:31,440
Four,

55
00:08:31,520 --> 00:08:32,840
three,

56
00:08:33,040 --> 00:08:34,320
two,

57
00:08:34,520 --> 00:08:35,640
one.

58
00:08:48,040 --> 00:08:51,440
All right, everybody. This is a raid.

59
00:08:51,520 --> 00:08:54,440
I'm a federal agent.
You're all under arrest.

60
00:08:54,920 --> 00:08:57,840
I want another cup of coffee.

61
00:09:09,120 --> 00:09:10,840
All right, Spats.

62
00:09:10,920 --> 00:09:13,520
- The services are over. Let's go.
- Go where?

63
00:09:13,720 --> 00:09:17,520
A country club for retired bootleggers.
I'm puttin' you up for membership.

64
00:09:17,720 --> 00:09:20,520
- I don't join nothin'.
- Oh, you'll like it there.

65
00:09:20,720 --> 00:09:25,120
I'll get the prison tailor to fit you
with a pair of special spats - striped.

66
00:09:25,240 --> 00:09:28,240
Big joke. What's the rap this time?

67
00:09:28,320 --> 00:09:32,320
Embalming people with coffee. 86 proof.

68
00:09:32,520 --> 00:09:34,440
Me? I'm just a customer.

69
00:09:34,520 --> 00:09:39,840
Oh, come on, Spats. We know you own
the joint. Mozarella's just frontin' for you.

70
00:09:39,920 --> 00:09:44,040
- Mozarella? Never heard of him.
- We got different information.

71
00:09:44,240 --> 00:09:46,920
From who? Toothpick Charlie maybe?

72
00:09:47,120 --> 00:09:49,720
Toothpick Charlie? Never heard of him.

73
00:09:51,840 --> 00:09:54,440
Buttermilk.

74
00:09:54,640 --> 00:09:57,120
Too smart to drink your own stuff, huh?

75
00:09:57,320 --> 00:10:00,120
Come on. On your feet.

76
00:10:00,320 --> 00:10:04,040
- You're wastin' the taxpayers' money.
- Call your lawyer if you wanna.

77
00:10:04,120 --> 00:10:06,920
These are my lawyers. All Harvard men.

78
00:10:15,040 --> 00:10:17,640
I wan' another cuppa coffee.

79
00:10:54,440 --> 00:10:57,840
That solves one problem. Now we don't
have to worry about who to pay first.

80
00:10:58,080 --> 00:11:00,760
- Quiet. I'm thinking.
- The landlady will lock us out.

81
00:11:00,960 --> 00:11:03,480
At Moe's Deli no
more knockwurst on credit.

82
00:11:03,560 --> 00:11:06,760
We can't borrow from the girls -
they're on the way to jail.

83
00:11:06,960 --> 00:11:10,160
I wonder how much Sam the bookie
will give us for our overcoats.

84
00:11:10,280 --> 00:11:14,760
Sam the bookie? Nothin' doin'.
You're not puttin' my overcoat on a dog.

85
00:11:14,880 --> 00:11:17,880
- Jerry, I told you, it's a sure thing.
- We will freeze.

86
00:11:17,960 --> 00:11:20,280
It is below zero. We'll get pneumonia.

87
00:11:20,480 --> 00:11:23,960
Look, stupid, he's 10-1.
Tomorrow we'll have 20 overcoats.

88
00:11:33,880 --> 00:11:35,560
Greased Lightning.

89
00:11:35,680 --> 00:11:39,360
- I oughta have my head examined.
- I thought you weren't talkin' to me.

90
00:11:39,560 --> 00:11:42,680
The bull fiddle's
dressed warmer than I am.

91
00:11:49,160 --> 00:11:50,880
- Anyzhing today?
- Nothing.

92
00:11:50,960 --> 00:11:52,560
Thank you.

93
00:11:54,960 --> 00:11:56,680
- Anyzhing today?
- Nothing.

94
00:11:56,880 --> 00:11:58,360
Thank you.

95
00:11:58,560 --> 00:12:02,680
I can't go on, Joe. I'm weak from hunger,
I got a fever, I got a hole in my shoe...

96
00:12:02,880 --> 00:12:05,480
If you gave me a chance,
we could be living like kings.

97
00:12:05,680 --> 00:12:07,680
- How?
- There's a dog running in the third.

98
00:12:07,880 --> 00:12:12,160
Galloping Ghost. He's 15-1 and it's
his kind of a track. He's a real mudder.

99
00:12:12,280 --> 00:12:14,760
What do you want from me?
My head on a plate?

100
00:12:14,960 --> 00:12:17,560
No, your bass.
If we hock that and my sax...

101
00:12:17,760 --> 00:12:21,280
Are you crazy? We're up the creek
and you wanna hock the paddle.

102
00:12:21,360 --> 00:12:24,360
All right, go ahead and starve.
What do I care? Freeze.

103
00:12:24,480 --> 00:12:27,080
- Anyzhing today?
- Oh, it's you.

104
00:12:27,160 --> 00:12:29,080
Well, you've got a lot of nerve.

105
00:12:29,280 --> 00:12:31,080
Thank you.

106
00:12:31,280 --> 00:12:33,160
Joe. Come back here.

107
00:12:37,160 --> 00:12:40,480
Nellie, baby, if it's about Saturday night,
I can explain.

108
00:12:40,680 --> 00:12:43,760
What a heel. I spend $4
to get my hair marcelled,

109
00:12:43,880 --> 00:12:45,880
I buy me a brand-new negligee,

110
00:12:45,960 --> 00:12:47,960
I bake him a great big pizza pie.

111
00:12:48,160 --> 00:12:50,960
- And where were you?
- Where were you?

112
00:12:51,160 --> 00:12:52,280
- With you.
- Me?

113
00:12:52,480 --> 00:12:54,280
Remember? You had this bad tooth.

114
00:12:54,480 --> 00:12:56,560
It was impacted. His jaw was swoll out.

115
00:12:56,680 --> 00:12:57,680
It was?

116
00:12:57,880 --> 00:12:59,760
Oh, yeah.

117
00:12:59,960 --> 00:13:03,280
- I took him for a blood transfusion.
- We have the same type blood.

118
00:13:03,360 --> 00:13:06,080
- Type O.
- Oh?

119
00:13:06,160 --> 00:13:10,080
- I'll make it up to you.
- You're makin' it up pretty good so far.

120
00:13:10,160 --> 00:13:14,480
As soon as we get a job, I'll take you
to the swellest restaurant in town.

121
00:13:14,560 --> 00:13:18,280
How about it? Has Poliakoff got
anyzhing for us? We're desperate.

122
00:13:18,360 --> 00:13:21,960
Well, it just so happens
he is looking for a bass.

123
00:13:22,080 --> 00:13:23,680
And a sax.

124
00:13:23,760 --> 00:13:25,280
Right?

125
00:13:25,360 --> 00:13:26,760
Right.

126
00:13:26,880 --> 00:13:29,560
- What's the job?
- Three weeks in Florida.

127
00:13:29,760 --> 00:13:33,480
At the Seminole-Ritz in Miami.
Transportation and expenses all paid.

128
00:13:33,680 --> 00:13:36,680
Isn't she a bit of terrific?
Let's see Poliakoff.

129
00:13:36,760 --> 00:13:40,280
- He's busy. You'll have to wait, boys.
- All right, we'll wait.

130
00:13:40,360 --> 00:13:42,880
Look, Gladys, it's three weeks in Florida.

131
00:13:42,960 --> 00:13:45,280
Sweet Sue and her Society Syncopators.

132
00:13:45,360 --> 00:13:48,360
They need a couple of girls
on sax and bass.

133
00:13:48,560 --> 00:13:52,160
Whaddaya mean, who is it?
It's Poliakoff. I got a job for ya.

134
00:13:52,280 --> 00:13:53,880
Gladys. Are ya there?

135
00:13:54,080 --> 00:13:56,160
Gladys!

136
00:13:56,360 --> 00:13:59,280
Meshugeneh.
Played 112 hours at a marathon dance.

137
00:13:59,480 --> 00:14:02,680
- Now she's in bed with nervous collapse.
- Tell her to move over.

138
00:14:02,760 --> 00:14:04,280
And Cora Jackson?

139
00:14:04,360 --> 00:14:07,800
Last I heard, she was playin'
with the Salvation Army.

140
00:14:07,920 --> 00:14:09,920
Drexel 9044.

141
00:14:10,000 --> 00:14:11,920
Those idiot broads.

142
00:14:12,120 --> 00:14:15,720
Here we are, packed and ready to leave
for Miami, and what happens?

143
00:14:15,800 --> 00:14:20,920
The sax runs off with a Bible salesman
and the bass gets pregnant.

144
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:22,920
Bienstock, I oughta fire you.

145
00:14:23,000 --> 00:14:26,120
Me? I'm the manager,
not the night watchman.

146
00:14:26,320 --> 00:14:28,800
Hello. Let me talk to Bessie Malone.

147
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:31,400
What's she doing in Philadelphia?

148
00:14:31,520 --> 00:14:33,800
On the level?

149
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:36,600
Bessie let her hair grow
and is playing with Stokowski.

150
00:14:36,720 --> 00:14:40,320
- Black Bottom Bessie?
- Schpielt zich mit der Philharmonic.

151
00:14:40,920 --> 00:14:42,320
How about Rosemary Schultz?

152
00:14:42,400 --> 00:14:44,520
Slashed her wrists when Valentino died.

153
00:14:44,600 --> 00:14:48,200
We might as well do the same
if we don't find two dames by tonight.

154
00:14:48,320 --> 00:14:52,520
We don't care where you find them.
Just get them on that train by 8 o'clock.

155
00:14:52,720 --> 00:14:56,400
The moment anyzhing turns up,
I'll give you a tinkle.

156
00:14:56,600 --> 00:14:59,200
Bye, Sig. I wonder
if I've got room for another ulcer.

157
00:14:59,400 --> 00:15:01,520
Nellie, get me long-distance.

158
00:15:01,720 --> 00:15:05,920
- Sig, we wanna talk to you.
- About the Florida job.

159
00:15:06,000 --> 00:15:08,320
- Nellie told us about it.
- Not too late, are we?

160
00:15:08,520 --> 00:15:10,720
What are ya? Comedians? Get out.

161
00:15:10,920 --> 00:15:13,600
The William Morris Agency in New York.

162
00:15:13,720 --> 00:15:17,320
- You need a bass and a sax?
- The instruments are right but you're not.

163
00:15:17,400 --> 00:15:18,720
I wanna speak to Mr Morris.

164
00:15:18,920 --> 00:15:21,320
- What's wrong with us?
- You're the wrong shape.

165
00:15:21,520 --> 00:15:25,400
- What do you want? Hunchbacks?
- It's not the backs that worry me.

166
00:15:25,600 --> 00:15:26,920
What kind of a band is it?

167
00:15:27,120 --> 00:15:29,320
- You gotta be under 25.
- We could pass for that.

168
00:15:29,400 --> 00:15:30,920
- And blond.
- We could dye our hair.

169
00:15:31,120 --> 00:15:32,320
And you gotta be girls.

170
00:15:32,520 --> 00:15:33,600
No, we couldn't.

171
00:15:33,720 --> 00:15:36,720
- Mr William Morris.
- You mean this is a girls' band?

172
00:15:36,800 --> 00:15:40,200
Yeah. Good old Nellie.
I could wring her neck.

173
00:15:40,400 --> 00:15:42,600
Let's talk this over. Why couldn't we do it?

174
00:15:42,800 --> 00:15:45,800
When we worked in the gypsy tearoom,
we wore gold earrings.

175
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:49,120
When you booked us with
the Hawaiian band, we wore grass skirts.

176
00:15:49,320 --> 00:15:52,320
- What's with him? He drinks?
- No, he ain't eatin' so good.

177
00:15:52,400 --> 00:15:54,400
His empty stomach has gone to his head.

178
00:15:54,600 --> 00:15:58,400
Joe, three weeks in Florida. We could
borrow clothes from the chorus girls.

179
00:15:58,520 --> 00:16:01,720
- You've flipped your wig.
- Now you're talking.

180
00:16:01,800 --> 00:16:04,320
We get second-hand wigs, a little padding.

181
00:16:04,400 --> 00:16:06,800
We call ourselves
Josephine and Geraldine.

182
00:16:07,000 --> 00:16:10,120
Josephine and Geraldine... Come on.

183
00:16:10,320 --> 00:16:12,720
If you wanna pick up
a little money tonight,

184
00:16:12,800 --> 00:16:16,720
at the University of Illinois
they're havin' a St Valentine's dance.

185
00:16:16,800 --> 00:16:18,320
We'll take it.

186
00:16:18,400 --> 00:16:21,120
$6 a man. Be on the campus
at Urbana at 8 o'clock.

187
00:16:21,200 --> 00:16:23,800
All the way to Urbana
for a one-night stand?

188
00:16:23,920 --> 00:16:26,920
It's $12. We can get
one of the overcoats out of hock.

189
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:30,520
Hello. Mr Morris?
This is Poliakoff in Chicago.

190
00:16:30,600 --> 00:16:33,320
You don't have two girl musicians
available, do you?

191
00:16:33,400 --> 00:16:34,920
A sax player and a bass?

192
00:16:35,120 --> 00:16:39,720
- If William Morris doesn't come through...
- Come on, Geraldine.

193
00:16:40,720 --> 00:16:43,720
It's 100 miles. It's snowin' outside.
How do we get there?

194
00:16:43,800 --> 00:16:45,600
- I'll find something.
- Like what?

195
00:16:45,800 --> 00:16:48,120
Don't crowd me.

196
00:16:48,200 --> 00:16:51,600
- How'd it go, girls?
- I oughta wring your neck.

197
00:16:51,720 --> 00:16:54,320
Please, Jerry. That's no way to talk.

198
00:16:55,000 --> 00:16:57,400
Nellie baby, what are you doin' tonight?

199
00:16:57,520 --> 00:17:01,120
- Tonight? Why?
- Cos I've got some plans.

200
00:17:01,200 --> 00:17:04,520
- I'm not doing anything.
- Really?

201
00:17:04,720 --> 00:17:08,600
I just thought I'd go home
and have some cold pizza.

202
00:17:08,800 --> 00:17:10,720
Then you'll be in all evening?

203
00:17:10,800 --> 00:17:12,520
Yes, Joe.

204
00:17:12,720 --> 00:17:14,720
Good. Then you won't
be needing your car.

205
00:17:14,800 --> 00:17:16,840
My car? Why, you...

206
00:17:19,560 --> 00:17:22,160
Isn't he a bit of terrific?

207
00:17:30,960 --> 00:17:34,360
We coulda had three weeks
in Florida, all expenses paid.

208
00:17:34,440 --> 00:17:37,040
Lyin' in the sun, palm trees, flyin' fish...

209
00:17:37,160 --> 00:17:39,160
Knock it off, will ya?

210
00:17:42,160 --> 00:17:45,240
Possible straight, possible nothing,
and a pair of eights.

211
00:17:48,240 --> 00:17:50,160
All right, drop 'em, you guys.

212
00:17:50,240 --> 00:17:52,440
- Drop what?
- We came for a car.

213
00:17:52,640 --> 00:17:55,040
- Oh, yeah?
- Yeah. Nellie Weinmeyer's car.

214
00:17:58,840 --> 00:17:59,960
Musicians.

215
00:18:00,160 --> 00:18:01,440
Wise guys.

216
00:18:01,640 --> 00:18:03,960
OK, let's go. Aces bet.

217
00:18:04,040 --> 00:18:06,840
It's a '25 Hupmobile, green, coupe... sir.

218
00:18:07,040 --> 00:18:09,240
- It's over here.
- Yeah, over here.

219
00:18:09,360 --> 00:18:14,160
- Want some gas?
- Yeah, about 40 cents' worth, please.

220
00:18:14,240 --> 00:18:17,560
- Put it on Miss Weinmeyer's bill?
- Yeah. Why not?

221
00:18:17,640 --> 00:18:20,160
And while you're at it, fill it up.

222
00:18:29,240 --> 00:18:31,760
All right, everybody. Hands up.

223
00:18:33,840 --> 00:18:35,760
Face the wall.

224
00:18:38,160 --> 00:18:40,160
You too, Toothpick.

225
00:18:40,240 --> 00:18:42,160
Come on.

226
00:18:43,840 --> 00:18:45,840
Come on.

227
00:18:56,040 --> 00:18:59,560
Hey. Join us.

228
00:19:10,240 --> 00:19:12,560
OK, boss.

229
00:19:24,440 --> 00:19:26,840
Hello, Charlie. Long time no see.

230
00:19:27,040 --> 00:19:30,840
- Spats, what are you doin' here?
- I just dropped in to pay my respects.

231
00:19:31,040 --> 00:19:33,360
- You don't owe me nothin'.
- I wouldn't say that.

232
00:19:33,560 --> 00:19:35,960
You recommended
my mortuary to your friends.

233
00:19:36,040 --> 00:19:39,360
- I don't know what you mean.
