Sugar, if you feel you're
coming down with something, my dear,

470
00:38:13,200 --> 00:38:16,000
the best thing in the world
is a shot of whiskey.

471
00:38:16,080 --> 00:38:18,880
- You've got some?
- I know where to get it.

472
00:38:19,000 --> 00:38:20,480
Don't move.

473
00:38:21,200 --> 00:38:23,400
- Hold on.
- OK.

474
00:38:44,280 --> 00:38:46,200
Up. Up.

475
00:38:51,480 --> 00:38:53,600
- Are you all right?
- I'm fine.

476
00:38:53,800 --> 00:38:56,600
- How's the bottle?
- Half-full.

477
00:38:58,000 --> 00:39:00,000
- You'd better get some cups.
- Cups?

478
00:39:10,000 --> 00:39:13,600
Oh, I tell you, my dear,
this is the only way to travel.

479
00:39:13,720 --> 00:39:16,320
Put on the lights.
I can't see what I'm doing.

480
00:39:16,520 --> 00:39:18,840
No lights. We don't want them to know.

481
00:39:19,040 --> 00:39:21,440
- But I might spill some.
- So spill it.

482
00:39:21,640 --> 00:39:24,440
Spills, thrills, laughs and games.

483
00:39:24,520 --> 00:39:27,120
This may even turn out
to be a surprise party.

484
00:39:27,240 --> 00:39:29,520
- What's the surprise?
- Not yet.

485
00:39:29,640 --> 00:39:32,040
- When?
- Better have a drink first.

486
00:39:32,120 --> 00:39:34,120
That'll put hair on your chest.

487
00:39:34,240 --> 00:39:36,240
No fair guessing.

488
00:39:37,520 --> 00:39:39,440
Is this a private clambake?

489
00:39:39,520 --> 00:39:41,440
It's private. Please, go away.

490
00:39:41,520 --> 00:39:43,720
Dolores, do you still have that vermouth?

491
00:39:43,840 --> 00:39:45,440
- Sure.
- Who needs vermouth?

492
00:39:45,520 --> 00:39:48,440
We've got bourbon.
We can make Manhattans.

493
00:39:48,520 --> 00:39:50,640
Manhattans? At this time of night?

494
00:39:50,720 --> 00:39:53,240
- Bring the cocktail shaker.
- Oh, Sugar.

495
00:39:53,320 --> 00:39:55,320
You're gonna spoil my surprise.

496
00:39:56,920 --> 00:39:59,440
- Hey, honey, what's up?
- Party in upper 7.

497
00:39:59,520 --> 00:40:03,440
- I'll get cheese and crackers.
- I'll get a shaker, you get a corkscrew.

498
00:40:03,520 --> 00:40:05,720
Hey, Rosella, there's a party in upper 7.

499
00:40:05,840 --> 00:40:07,640
- You got a corkscrew?
- Stella has.

500
00:40:07,840 --> 00:40:10,240
Go get some paper cups.

501
00:40:10,320 --> 00:40:12,840
Hey, there's a party in upper 7.

502
00:40:17,520 --> 00:40:20,720
- Here's the vermouth.
- This is a private party. Please go away.

503
00:40:20,840 --> 00:40:23,440
I brought some cheese and crackers.

504
00:40:23,520 --> 00:40:27,240
- Will ten cups be enough?
- This is a party for two. Ten cups?

505
00:40:28,520 --> 00:40:32,640
- Please, girls. Will you stop this?
- Could you use some Southern Comfort?

506
00:40:33,720 --> 00:40:36,920
Girls, you'll wake up
the neighbours downstairs.

507
00:40:37,520 --> 00:40:39,440
Watch that corkscrew.

508
00:40:39,640 --> 00:40:42,520
- Here's a cracker.
- No crackers in bed.

509
00:40:42,640 --> 00:40:45,040
Will you girls go away
and form your own party?

510
00:40:45,120 --> 00:40:47,040
Here's the cocktail shaker.

511
00:40:47,240 --> 00:40:50,320
- I wish we had ice.
- Easy on the vermouth.

512
00:40:50,520 --> 00:40:54,440
13 girls in a berth is bad luck.
12 of you will have to get out.

513
00:40:54,520 --> 00:40:57,840
- Pass me the peanut butter.
- Anyone for salami?

514
00:40:57,920 --> 00:41:00,240
No more food.
I'll have ants in the morning.

515
00:41:01,520 --> 00:41:05,320
Hey. Have you got any
maraschino cherries on you?

516
00:41:05,520 --> 00:41:07,440
Never mind.

517
00:41:13,240 --> 00:41:15,120
Maraschino cherries?

518
00:41:23,920 --> 00:41:25,440
What's going on here?

519
00:41:25,520 --> 00:41:29,120
Daphne. Daphne, where are you?

520
00:41:29,720 --> 00:41:32,640
It's not my fault. I didn't invite 'em.

521
00:41:32,720 --> 00:41:35,120
Come on, girls, break it up.

522
00:41:35,240 --> 00:41:38,920
You heard Josephine.
Girls. Everybody out.

523
00:41:39,840 --> 00:41:42,240
- Not you, Sugar.
- I'm going to get some ice.

524
00:41:42,440 --> 00:41:44,320
Get out.

525
00:41:44,520 --> 00:41:47,120
That's right, Sugar.
Now the rest of you. Out.

526
00:41:48,720 --> 00:41:51,320
- Come on in. The water's fine.
- Have a Manhattan.

527
00:41:51,440 --> 00:41:54,840
- Pipe down. We'll all be fired.
- Sugar. Don't leave me here alone.

528
00:41:54,920 --> 00:41:57,440
Come on, kids. It's two o'clock.

529
00:41:57,520 --> 00:42:00,640
You've had your fun.
The party's over. Everybody go home.

530
00:42:01,520 --> 00:42:04,640
- What's this?
- Josephine, over here before it melts.

531
00:42:11,120 --> 00:42:13,320
Put it here.

532
00:42:13,440 --> 00:42:15,720
Sugar, you're gonna
get into a lot of trouble.

533
00:42:15,920 --> 00:42:17,520
You'd better keep a lookout.

534
00:42:17,640 --> 00:42:19,680
If Bienstock catches you again...

535
00:42:19,720 --> 00:42:21,880
What's the matter with you, anyway?

536
00:42:21,960 --> 00:42:23,880
I'm not very bright, I guess.

537
00:42:24,080 --> 00:42:26,160
I wouldn't say that. Careless, maybe.

538
00:42:26,360 --> 00:42:30,960
No, just dumb. If I had any brains, I
wouldn't be with this crummy girls' band.

539
00:42:31,160 --> 00:42:32,880
Well, why'd you take this job?

540
00:42:32,960 --> 00:42:35,680
I used to sing with male bands,
but I can't afford it any more.

541
00:42:35,760 --> 00:42:38,160
Have you ever been with a male band?

542
00:42:38,280 --> 00:42:39,680
Who, me?

543
00:42:39,760 --> 00:42:41,280
That's what I'm running away from.

544
00:42:41,480 --> 00:42:44,880
I worked with six in the last two years.
Oh, brother.

545
00:42:45,080 --> 00:42:46,880
- Rough?
- I'll say.

546
00:42:47,080 --> 00:42:49,880
- You can't trust those guys.
- I can't trust myself.

547
00:42:49,960 --> 00:42:52,480
I have this thing about saxophone players.

548
00:42:52,560 --> 00:42:54,480
Especially tenor sax.

549
00:42:56,360 --> 00:42:59,760
- Really?
- I don't know why, but they curdle me.

550
00:42:59,960 --> 00:43:03,280
All they have to do is play eight bars of
"Come To Me, My Melancholy Baby"

551
00:43:03,480 --> 00:43:07,080
and I get goose-pimply all over,
and I come to 'em.

552
00:43:07,160 --> 00:43:09,360
- That so?
- Every time.

553
00:43:10,960 --> 00:43:13,080
You know, I play tenor sax.

554
00:43:13,160 --> 00:43:16,960
But you're a girl - thank goodness.
That's why I joined this band.

555
00:43:17,080 --> 00:43:21,160
Safety first. Anyzhing
to get away from those bums.

556
00:43:21,280 --> 00:43:24,360
You don't know what they're like.
You fall for 'em.

557
00:43:24,480 --> 00:43:27,360
You think this is gonna be
the biggest thing since the Graf Zeppelin.

558
00:43:27,560 --> 00:43:29,880
The next thing you know,
they're borrowing money from you,

559
00:43:29,960 --> 00:43:33,080
spending it on other dames
and betting on horses.

560
00:43:33,280 --> 00:43:34,560
You don't say.

561
00:43:34,760 --> 00:43:37,880
Then one morning you wake up,
the guy's gone, the sax's gone.

562
00:43:38,080 --> 00:43:42,480
All that's left is a pair of old socks
and a tube of toothpaste all squeezed out.

563
00:43:42,680 --> 00:43:46,880
You pull yourself together, you go on to
the next job, the next saxophone player.

564
00:43:46,960 --> 00:43:49,080
It's the same thing all over again.

565
00:43:49,280 --> 00:43:52,760
You see what I mean? Not very bright.

566
00:43:52,960 --> 00:43:54,960
Brains aren't everyzhing.

567
00:43:55,680 --> 00:43:59,080
I can tell you one thing. It's not
gonna happen to me again - ever.

568
00:43:59,160 --> 00:44:02,080
I'm tired of getting
the fuzzy end of the lollipop.

569
00:44:02,160 --> 00:44:06,080
Ice. What's keeping the ice?
The natives are getting restless.

570
00:44:06,160 --> 00:44:08,880
- How about a couple of drinks for us?
- Sure.

571
00:44:10,160 --> 00:44:13,280
- You know, I'm gonna be 25 in June.
- You are?

572
00:44:13,360 --> 00:44:15,960
That's a quarter of a century.
Makes a girl think.

573
00:44:16,080 --> 00:44:17,680
- About what?
- The future.

574
00:44:17,760 --> 00:44:21,080
You know - like a husband. That's why
I'm glad we're going to Florida.

575
00:44:21,280 --> 00:44:24,360
- What's in Florida?
- Millionaires. Flocks of them.

576
00:44:24,480 --> 00:44:26,760
They all go south for the winter, like birds.

577
00:44:26,960 --> 00:44:30,080
- Gonna catch yourself a rich bird?
- I don't care how rich he is.

578
00:44:30,160 --> 00:44:34,160
As long as he has a yacht, a private
railroad car and his own toothpaste.

579
00:44:34,280 --> 00:44:37,280
- You're entitled.
- Maybe you'll meet one too, Josephine.

580
00:44:37,360 --> 00:44:41,080
With money like Rockefeller and
shoulders like Johnny Weissmuller.

581
00:44:41,160 --> 00:44:43,760
- I want mine to wear glasses.
- Glasses?

582
00:44:43,880 --> 00:44:47,680
Men who wear glasses are so much
more gentle and sweet and helpless.

583
00:44:47,760 --> 00:44:50,880
- Haven't you ever noticed it?
- Yeah, now that you mention.

584
00:44:51,080 --> 00:44:53,560
They get those weak eyes from reading.

585
00:44:53,760 --> 00:44:58,080
Those long, tiny little columns
in The Wall Street Journal.

586
00:44:58,760 --> 00:45:01,760
That bass fiddle, she sure
knows how to throw a party.

587
00:45:01,880 --> 00:45:04,680
Hot-diggety-dog.

588
00:45:04,760 --> 00:45:07,160
Well, happy days.

589
00:45:07,360 --> 00:45:12,680
I hope this time you wind up
with the sweet end of the lollipop.

590
00:45:14,360 --> 00:45:16,360
So the one-legged jockey said...

591
00:45:16,480 --> 00:45:18,480
What did he say?

592
00:45:18,560 --> 00:45:23,960
So the one-legged jockey said: "Don't
worry about me, baby. I ride side-saddle."

593
00:45:30,600 --> 00:45:33,120
I'm terribly sorry. I seem to have hiccups.

594
00:45:33,200 --> 00:45:35,520
Hey, let's rub some ice on her neck.

595
00:45:35,600 --> 00:45:37,600
I think... Ow. You dropped it.

596
00:45:37,720 --> 00:45:39,320
Oh, that's cold.

597
00:45:39,520 --> 00:45:43,000
- Oh, no, please. Don't do that.
- She's ticklish.

598
00:45:46,400 --> 00:45:49,000
Help. Please. Help. Help.

599
00:45:49,120 --> 00:45:50,400
Josephine.

600
00:45:50,520 --> 00:45:53,920
Please stop that. Stop that.

601
00:46:04,120 --> 00:46:06,120
- What happened?
- Search me.

602
00:46:06,200 --> 00:46:08,120
I mean, I'll see.

603
00:46:18,200 --> 00:46:20,520
All right, what's goin' on around here?

604
00:46:20,800 --> 00:46:22,520
Bienstock!

605
00:46:23,400 --> 00:46:25,400
Are we in Florida?

606
00:47:08,600 --> 00:47:10,120
Sugar?

607
00:47:10,200 --> 00:47:12,520
Here. I'll carry the instruments.

608
00:47:12,720 --> 00:47:15,000
- Thank you, Daphne.
- Thank you, Daphne.

609
00:47:15,120 --> 00:47:17,320
Isn't she a sweetheart?

610
00:47:23,320 --> 00:47:25,200
How do you do?

611
00:47:28,200 --> 00:47:29,400
Zowie!

612
00:47:29,600 --> 00:47:32,920
There they are. More millionaires
than you can shake a stick at.

613
00:47:33,120 --> 00:47:34,920
I bet there isn't one under 75.

614
00:47:35,000 --> 00:47:38,200
That's three quarters of a century.
Makes a girl think.

615
00:47:38,400 --> 00:47:40,920
Let's hope they brought
their grandsons along.

616
00:47:41,000 --> 00:47:42,520
Yes.

617
00:47:51,200 --> 00:47:53,120
Pardon me, miss.

618
00:47:54,800 --> 00:47:56,720
- May I?
- Help yourself.

619
00:47:56,920 --> 00:47:59,520
I'm Osgood Fielding the Third.

620
00:47:59,600 --> 00:48:01,600
I'm Cinderella the Second.

621
00:48:01,720 --> 00:48:06,120
If there's one thing I admire,
it's a girl with a shapely ankle.

622
00:48:06,800 --> 00:48:08,720
Me, too. Bye-bye.

623
00:48:09,200 --> 00:48:12,200
- Let me carry one of the instruments.
- Oh, thank you.

624
00:48:12,400 --> 00:48:14,720
Aren't you a sweetheart.

625
00:48:19,320 --> 00:48:22,400
It certainly is delightful
having young blood around here.

626
00:48:22,600 --> 00:48:23,920
Personally, I'm type O.

627
00:48:24,120 --> 00:48:26,600
I've always been fascinated
by show business.

628
00:48:26,800 --> 00:48:28,120
Is that so?

629
00:48:28,200 --> 00:48:31,400
As a matter of fact,
it's cost my family quite a bit of money.

630
00:48:31,520 --> 00:48:34,200
- Oh, you invest in shows?
- Showgirls.

631
00:48:34,400 --> 00:48:37,160
- I've been married seven or eight times.
- You're not sure?

632
00:48:37,320 --> 00:48:39,160
Mama is keeping score.

633
00:48:39,360 --> 00:48:41,960
- She's getting annoyed with me.
- I wouldn't wonder.

634
00:48:42,160 --> 00:48:45,760
So when George White's Scandals
opened, she packed me off to Florida.

635
00:48:45,840 --> 00:48:50,440
She thinks I'm out on my yacht,
deep-sea fishing.

636
00:48:51,360 --> 00:48:55,560
Well, pull in your reel, Mr Fielding.
You're barking up the wrong fish.

637
00:48:56,840 --> 00:48:59,760
If I promise not to be a naughty boy,
how about dinner?

638
00:48:59,960 --> 00:49:02,840
- I'm sorry. I'll be on the bandstand.
- Oh, of course.

639
00:49:03,040 --> 00:49:05,440
- Which instrument do you play?
- Bull fiddle.

640
00:49:05,560 --> 00:49:06,960
Oh, fascinating.

641
00:49:07,040 --> 00:49:09,240
Do you use a bow, or do you just pluck it?

642
00:49:10,240 --> 00:49:13,240
Most of the time, I slap it.

643
00:49:13,360 --> 00:49:15,760
You must be quite a girl.

644
00:49:15,840 --> 00:49:17,560
Wanna bet?

645
00:49:17,760 --> 00:49:21,360
My last wife was an acrobatic dancer.
Sort of a contortionist.

646
00:49:21,440 --> 00:49:24,760
She could smoke a cigarette
while holding it between her toes.

647
00:49:24,840 --> 00:49:26,240
Zowie!

648
00:49:26,360 --> 00:49:28,360
- But Mama broke it up.
- Why?

649
00:49:28,440 --> 00:49:30,560
She doesn't approve of girls who smoke.

650
00:49:32,760 --> 00:49:34,760
- Bye-bye, Mr Fielding.
- Bye-bye?

651
00:49:34,840 --> 00:49:37,760
- This is where I get off.
- Oh, no. No, no, no.

652
00:49:37,960 --> 00:49:39,840
You don't get off that easy.

653
00:49:40,040 --> 00:49:42,440
All right, driver.
Once around the park, slowly.

654
00:49:42,640 --> 00:49:44,960
And keep your eyes on the road.

655
00:49:53,960 --> 00:49:56,760
What kind of a girl
do you think I am, Mr Fielding?

656
00:49:58,160 --> 00:50:01,160
- Oh, please. It won't happen again.
- I'll say.

657
00:50:01,360 --> 00:50:03,760
- Please, come back.
- I'll walk, thank you.

658
00:50:03,840 --> 00:50:05,840
Please, miss...

659
00:50:08,360 --> 00:50:09,760
Zowie!

660
00:50:10,360 --> 00:50:12,760
All right, girls. Here are
your room assignments.

661
00:50:12,960 --> 00:50:15,560
My glasses. Where are my glasses?

662
00:50:16,640 --> 00:50:18,640
Olga and Mary Lou are in 412.

663
00:50:18,840 --> 00:50:22,160
And, Mary Lou, do up your kimono
when you ring for room service.

664
00:50:22,240 --> 00:50:24,360
Josephine and Daphne are in 413.

665
00:50:24,440 --> 00:50:27,360
- Dolores and Sugar in 414.
- Me and Sugar?

666
00:50:27,560 --> 00:50:29,760
What did you expect?
A one-legged jockey?

667
00:50:29,960 --> 00:50:31,440
Rosella and Emily in 415...

668
00:50:32,360 --> 00:50:34,560
- I wish they'd put us in the same room.
- So do I.

669
00:50:34,760 --> 00:50:38,160
But don't worry about it, Sugar.
We'll see a lot of each other.

670
00:50:39,440 --> 00:50:43,560
414... That's the same room number
I had in Cincinnati,

671
00:50:43,760 --> 00:50:45,760
my last time around with a male band.

672
00:50:45,840 --> 00:50:47,640
What a heel he was.

673
00:50:47,760 --> 00:50:51,360
- A saxophone player?
- What else? Was I ever crazy about him.

674
00:50:51,440 --> 00:50:54,240
At two in the morning he sent me down
for hot dogs and potato salad.

675
00:50:54,440 --> 00:50:57,040
They were out of potato salad,
so I brought coleslaw.

676
00:50:57,160 --> 00:51:00,760
- So he threw it right in my face.
- Forget saxophone players.

677
00:51:00,840 --> 00:51:03,440
You're gonna meet
a millionaire - a young one.

678
00:51:03,560 --> 00:51:06,840
- What makes you so sure?
- My feminine intuition.

679
00:51:14,760 --> 00:51:16,640
Oh. Are these your bags?

680
00:51:18,040 --> 00:51:20,840
- And that one, too.
- OK, doll.

681
00:51:21,840 --> 00:51:25,240
- I suppose you want a tip.
- Forget it, doll.

682
00:51:25,360 --> 00:51:30,240
After all, you work here and I work here.
It's nice to have you with the organisation.

683
00:51:30,440 --> 00:51:32,560
- Bye-bye.
- Listen, doll.

684
00:51:32,760 --> 00:51:35,440
- What time do you get off tonight?
- Why?

685
00:51:35,560 --> 00:51:38,640
I'm workin' the night shift and
I got a bottle of gin stashed away.

686
00:51:38,840 --> 00:51:42,160
- When there's a lull...
- Aren't you a little young for that, sonny?

687
00:51:42,240 --> 00:51:46,000
Oh, you wanna see my driver's licence?

688
00:51:46,800 --> 00:51:51,600
- Get lost, will you?
- That's the way I like 'em - big and sassy.

689
00:51:52,400 --> 00:51:54,600
Oh, and... get rid of your roommate.

690
00:52:09,080 --> 00:52:10,800
- Dirty old man.
- What happened?

691
00:52:10,880 --> 00:52:14,000
- I got pinched in the elevator.
- See how the other half lives?

692
00:52:14,200 --> 00:52:15,600
I'm not even pretty.

693
00:52:15,680 --> 00:52:19,800
They don't care. You're wearing a skirt.
It's like waving a red flag to a bull.

694
00:52:19,880 --> 00:52:22,600
I'm sick of being the flag.
I wanna be a bull again.

695
00:52:22,680 --> 00:52:24,600
- Let's blow.
- Blow where?

696
00:52:24,800 --> 00:52:28,000
You promised me that the minute
we hit Florida we'd beat it.

697
00:52:28,080 --> 00:52:31,600
- How can we? We're broke.
- We can find another band. A male band.

698
00:52:31,800 --> 00:52:36,800
Spats Colombo is looking for us
in every male band in the country.

699
00:52:36,880 --> 00:52:40,080
- It's humiliating.
- So you got pinched. So what?

700
00:52:40,280 --> 00:52:42,880
Would you rather be
picking lead out of your navel?

701
00:52:43,000 --> 00:52:44,880
But how long can we keep this up?

702
00:52:45,000 --> 00:52:47,400
What's the beef? We're sittin' pretty.

703
00:52:47,600 --> 00:52:50,880
Look. We get room and board.
We're getting paid every week. Look.

704
00:52:51,000 --> 00:52:53,200
Look at the palm trees, flying fish...

705
00:52:53,400 --> 00:52:55,480
What are you givin' me with flyin' fish?

706
00:52:55,600 --> 00:52:58,000
I know why you wanna stay.
You're after Sugar.

707
00:52:58,080 --> 00:53:00,880
- Me, after Sugar?
- I saw the both of you in that bus.

708
00:53:01,000 --> 00:53:04,800
All lovey-dovey and whisperin'
and borrowin' each other's lipstick.

709
00:53:04,880 --> 00:53:07,400
- What are you saying? Me and Sugar?
