710
00:53:07,600 --> 00:53:11,080
- We're just like sisters.
- Well, I'm your fairy godmother.

711
00:53:11,200 --> 00:53:13,680
And I'm gonna keep an eye on you.

712
00:53:14,600 --> 00:53:16,880
Are you decent?

713
00:53:21,400 --> 00:53:23,280
Come in.

714
00:53:24,000 --> 00:53:27,000
You girls seen a brown bag
with a white stripe and my initials?

715
00:53:27,080 --> 00:53:28,680
It has all my resort clothes.

716
00:53:28,800 --> 00:53:31,200
- No, we haven't.
- I can't understand it.

717
00:53:31,280 --> 00:53:33,880
First my glasses disappear,
then one of my suitcases.

718
00:53:34,000 --> 00:53:35,880
- Where's my ukulele?
- Now a ukulele.

719
00:53:36,000 --> 00:53:40,400
- There must be a sneak thief around here.
- Oh. Here it is. Hi, Sug.

720
00:53:40,480 --> 00:53:44,200
- We're going for a swim. Coming?
- A swim. Oh, you betcha.

721
00:53:44,400 --> 00:53:47,000
You haven't got a bathing suit.

722
00:53:47,080 --> 00:53:48,880
I don't have one either.

723
00:53:49,080 --> 00:53:52,800
- She doesn't have one either. You don't?
- We can rent some at the bathhouse.

724
00:53:52,880 --> 00:53:56,280
- How about you, Josephine?
- I think I'll soak in a hot tub.

725
00:53:56,400 --> 00:54:00,400
- On a day like this? It's lovely out.
- Yeah, well, let her soak. Come on.

726
00:54:00,480 --> 00:54:03,680
- Don't get burned, Daphne.
- Oh, I've got suntan lotion.

727
00:54:03,800 --> 00:54:09,000
See? She'll rub it on me, I'll rub it on her,
we'll rub it on each other. Bye-bye.

728
00:55:08,320 --> 00:55:12,240
Daphne. Cut it out.
What do you think you're doing?

729
00:55:12,440 --> 00:55:15,240
Just a little trick
I picked up in the elevator.

730
00:55:15,320 --> 00:55:18,320
Ooh, look out. Here comes a big one.

731
00:55:47,320 --> 00:55:50,240
Daphne. I had no idea
you were such a big girl.

732
00:55:50,320 --> 00:55:52,920
You should've seen me
before I went on a diet.

733
00:55:53,120 --> 00:55:55,040
I mean your shoulders and your arms.

734
00:55:55,240 --> 00:55:57,320
It's carrying that bull fiddle around.

735
00:55:57,520 --> 00:55:59,840
- There's one thing I envy you for.
- What's that?

736
00:56:00,040 --> 00:56:01,920
You're so flat-chested.

737
00:56:02,120 --> 00:56:04,840
Clothes hang better on you
than they do on me.

738
00:56:04,920 --> 00:56:06,840
Watch out, Daphne.

739
00:56:07,040 --> 00:56:09,440
Sugar, come on. Let's play ball.

740
00:56:10,840 --> 00:56:12,520
Junior, time for your nap.

741
00:56:12,720 --> 00:56:14,840
No. I wanna play.

742
00:56:15,040 --> 00:56:17,120
You heard your mother, Junior. Scram!

743
00:56:17,320 --> 00:56:19,920
This beach ain't big enough
for the both of us.

744
00:56:20,040 --> 00:56:22,120
Mommy!

745
00:56:22,320 --> 00:56:23,520
Here we go.

746
00:56:23,640 --> 00:56:26,520
I like coffee, I like tea.

747
00:56:26,720 --> 00:56:30,240
How many boys are stuck on me?

748
00:56:30,720 --> 00:56:33,440
One, two, three,

749
00:56:33,640 --> 00:56:36,720
four, five, six, seven...

750
00:56:42,720 --> 00:56:45,320
I'm terribly sorry.
You're not hurt, are you?

751
00:56:45,440 --> 00:56:47,720
- I don't think so.
- I wish you'd make sure.

752
00:56:47,920 --> 00:56:49,840
Because when people find out who I am,

753
00:56:50,040 --> 00:56:54,640
they hire a shyster lawyer and sue me
for three quarters of a million dollars.

754
00:56:54,840 --> 00:56:58,120
- I won't sue you, no matter who you are.
- Thank you.

755
00:57:00,440 --> 00:57:02,320
- Who are you?
- Now, really!

756
00:57:04,640 --> 00:57:06,040
Sugar!

757
00:57:06,520 --> 00:57:08,320
Come on.

758
00:57:08,520 --> 00:57:09,640
Honestly.

759
00:57:10,920 --> 00:57:12,640
Cheerio.

760
00:57:17,320 --> 00:57:20,240
- Haven't I seen you somewhere before?
- Not very likely.

761
00:57:20,320 --> 00:57:22,720
- Are you staying at the hotel?
- Not at all.

762
00:57:22,920 --> 00:57:24,840
Your face is familiar.

763
00:57:24,920 --> 00:57:27,440
You may have seen it
in newspapers or magazines.

764
00:57:27,520 --> 00:57:30,240
- Vanity Fair.
- That must be it.

765
00:57:30,320 --> 00:57:33,840
Would you mind moving a little?
You're blocking my view.

766
00:57:34,040 --> 00:57:35,040
Of what?

767
00:57:35,240 --> 00:57:39,120
They run up a red-and-white flag
on the yacht when it's time for cocktails.

768
00:57:39,320 --> 00:57:41,240
You own a yacht?

769
00:57:42,120 --> 00:57:44,040
Which one is it? The big one?

770
00:57:44,720 --> 00:57:45,720
Certainly not.

771
00:57:45,920 --> 00:57:50,440
With all the world unrest, nobody should
have a yacht that sleeps more than 12.

772
00:57:50,520 --> 00:57:52,440
I quite agree.

773
00:57:52,520 --> 00:57:54,640
Tell me, who runs up that flag?

774
00:57:54,720 --> 00:57:57,320
- Your wife?
- No, my flag steward.

775
00:57:57,520 --> 00:58:00,520
Who mixes the cocktails? Your wife?

776
00:58:00,640 --> 00:58:02,680
No, my cocktail steward.

777
00:58:02,760 --> 00:58:05,080
Look, if you're interested in
whether I am married or not...

778
00:58:05,280 --> 00:58:07,960
- Oh, I'm not interested at all.
- Well, I'm not.

779
00:58:08,560 --> 00:58:11,160
That's very interesting.

780
00:58:13,760 --> 00:58:16,480
- How's the stock market?
- Up, up, up.

781
00:58:16,560 --> 00:58:19,160
I'll bet while we were talking,
you made $100,000?

782
00:58:19,360 --> 00:58:21,280
Could be. You play the market?

783
00:58:21,360 --> 00:58:24,480
- No, the ukulele. And I sing, too.
- For your own amusement?

784
00:58:24,680 --> 00:58:26,560
We are appearing at the hotel.

785
00:58:26,680 --> 00:58:28,760
Sweet Sue and her Society Syncopators.

786
00:58:28,880 --> 00:58:32,880
- You're society girls.
- Oh, yes, quite. Bryn Mawr, Vassar...

787
00:58:33,080 --> 00:58:35,080
We're just doing this for a lark.

788
00:58:35,680 --> 00:58:39,680
Syncopators. Does that mean you play
that very fast music... jazz?

789
00:58:39,760 --> 00:58:42,360
Yeah. Real hot.

790
00:58:42,480 --> 00:58:45,880
I guess some like it hot.
I personally prefer classical music.

791
00:58:46,680 --> 00:58:47,560
I do, too.

792
00:58:47,760 --> 00:58:52,680
As a matter of fact, I spent three years
at the Sheboygan Conservatory of Music.

793
00:58:52,760 --> 00:58:56,480
Good school. Your family
doesn't object to your career?

794
00:58:56,560 --> 00:58:59,880
They do indeed. Daddy threatened
to cut me off without a cent.

795
00:58:59,960 --> 00:59:01,680
But I don't care. It was such a bore.

796
00:59:01,760 --> 00:59:04,080
- Coming-out parties.
- Inauguration balls.

797
00:59:04,160 --> 00:59:06,080
- Opening at the opera.
- Riding to hounds.

798
00:59:06,280 --> 00:59:08,960
And always the same 400.

799
00:59:09,160 --> 00:59:11,760
It's amazing we never
ran into each other before.

800
00:59:11,880 --> 00:59:14,760
I'd have remembered
anybody as attractive as you.

801
00:59:14,880 --> 00:59:18,480
You're very kind. I'll bet
you're also gentle and helpless.

802
00:59:18,560 --> 00:59:19,960
I beg your pardon?

803
00:59:20,080 --> 00:59:22,560
You see, I have a theory
about men who wear glasses.

804
00:59:22,760 --> 00:59:25,880
- What theory?
- I'll tell you when I know you better.

805
00:59:25,960 --> 00:59:28,560
- What are you doing tonight?
- Tonight?

806
00:59:28,680 --> 00:59:31,560
Maybe you could come
to the hotel and hear us play.

807
00:59:31,760 --> 00:59:34,480
- I'd like to, but that would be difficult.
- Why?

808
00:59:34,560 --> 00:59:37,880
I only come ashore twice a day
when the tide goes out.

809
00:59:37,960 --> 00:59:40,680
It's on account of these shells.
That's my hobby.

810
00:59:40,880 --> 00:59:43,680
- You collect shells?
- So did my father and grandfather.

811
00:59:43,880 --> 00:59:46,280
You might say we had
a passion for shells.

812
00:59:46,360 --> 00:59:48,760
That's why we named
the oil company after it.

813
00:59:50,280 --> 00:59:54,680
- Shell Oil?
- Please, no names. Just call me Junior.

814
00:59:54,880 --> 00:59:56,880
Sugar!

815
00:59:56,960 --> 00:59:58,360
Time to change for dinner.

816
00:59:58,480 --> 01:00:01,680
Run along, Daphne dear.
I'll catch up with you later.

817
01:00:12,080 --> 01:00:14,280
What, young lady?
What are you staring at?

818
01:00:14,560 --> 01:00:16,160
Happens to me all the time.

819
01:00:16,360 --> 01:00:19,480
I recognised him, too.
His picture was in Vanity Fair.

820
01:00:19,560 --> 01:00:22,880
- Would you move along, please?
- Yes. You're in his way.

821
01:00:22,960 --> 01:00:25,480
He's waiting for a signal from his yacht.

822
01:00:25,560 --> 01:00:27,360
His yacht?

823
01:00:27,560 --> 01:00:30,880
It sleeps 12. This is my friend Daphne.
She's a Vassar girl.

824
01:00:31,480 --> 01:00:32,560
I'm a what?

825
01:00:32,760 --> 01:00:34,680
Or was it Bryn Mawr?

826
01:00:35,760 --> 01:00:39,480
I heard a very sad story
about a girl who went to Bryn Mawr.

827
01:00:39,680 --> 01:00:41,280
She squealed on her roommate

828
01:00:41,480 --> 01:00:44,480
and they found her strangled
with her own brassiere.

829
01:00:44,560 --> 01:00:49,480
Yes. We have to be very careful
whom we pick for a roommate. Hm?

830
01:00:49,560 --> 01:00:51,480
Well, I think I'd better be going.

831
01:00:51,680 --> 01:00:53,680
It was delightful meeting you both.

832
01:00:53,760 --> 01:00:56,760
- You will come and hear us play?
- If it's at all possible.

833
01:00:56,880 --> 01:00:59,080
Do come. It'll be such fun.

834
01:00:59,160 --> 01:01:02,080
- And bring your yacht.
- Come on, Daphne.

835
01:01:07,880 --> 01:01:12,000
- How about that guy?!
- Hands off. I saw him first.

836
01:01:12,200 --> 01:01:16,800
Sugar, a little advice. If I were a girl,
and I am, I'd watch my step.

837
01:01:17,000 --> 01:01:19,720
If I'd been watching my step,
I never would have met him.

838
01:01:19,800 --> 01:01:23,520
- I can't wait to tell Josephine.
- Yeah, Josephine...

839
01:01:23,600 --> 01:01:26,200
I can't wait to see her face.
Will she be surprised.

840
01:01:26,400 --> 01:01:28,800
Neither can I.
Let's go tell her right now.

841
01:01:29,000 --> 01:01:31,320
- We don't have to run.
- Oh yes, we do.

842
01:01:39,520 --> 01:01:41,400
Josephine. Yoo-hoo.

843
01:01:42,400 --> 01:01:45,000
- I guess she's not here.
- Isn't that funny. Josie!

844
01:01:45,120 --> 01:01:47,000
I can't imagine where she'd be.

845
01:01:47,200 --> 01:01:49,120
- I'll be back later.
- Oh, no. You wait.

846
01:01:49,200 --> 01:01:51,320
I have a feeling
she'll show up any minute.

847
01:01:51,400 --> 01:01:55,520
- Believe it or not, Josephine predicted it.
- Yes. This is one for Ripley.

848
01:01:55,600 --> 01:01:58,520
- Do you suppose she went shopping?
- Shopping. That's it.

849
01:01:58,720 --> 01:02:03,120
Something tells me she's gonna come
through that door in a brand-new outfit.

850
01:02:15,800 --> 01:02:19,000
- Josephine.
- Oh. I didn't hear you come in.

851
01:02:25,600 --> 01:02:30,120
- Have a good time, girls?
- The most wonderful thing happened.

852
01:02:30,320 --> 01:02:31,800
- What?
- Guess.

853
01:02:32,000 --> 01:02:36,000
- They repealed Prohibition?
- Oh, you can do better than that.

854
01:02:36,600 --> 01:02:38,920
- I met one of them.
- One of whom?

855
01:02:39,000 --> 01:02:42,800
Shell Oil Junior. He's got millions,
glasses and a yacht.

856
01:02:43,000 --> 01:02:44,320
You don't say.

857
01:02:44,400 --> 01:02:46,200
He's not only got a yacht.
He's got a bicycle.

858
01:02:46,400 --> 01:02:48,320
Daphne.

859
01:02:48,400 --> 01:02:50,400
Go on. Tell me all about him.

860
01:02:50,520 --> 01:02:53,520
Well, he's young and he's handsome.
He's a bachelor.

861
01:02:53,720 --> 01:02:58,120
He's a real gentleman.
You know. Not one of these grabbers.

862
01:02:58,200 --> 01:03:00,520
Maybe you'd better go after him
if you don't want to lose him.

863
01:03:00,720 --> 01:03:04,600
I'm not gonna let this one get away.
He's so cute. He collects shells.

864
01:03:04,800 --> 01:03:07,120
Shells? Whatever for?

865
01:03:07,200 --> 01:03:10,320
Oh, you know. The old shell game?

866
01:03:10,400 --> 01:03:12,000
Daphne, you're bothering us.

867
01:03:12,120 --> 01:03:14,720
- Anyway, you're gonna meet him tonight.
- I am?

868
01:03:14,800 --> 01:03:16,920
He said he'd come
to hear us play - maybe.

869
01:03:17,120 --> 01:03:21,400
What do you mean, maybe? I saw the way
he looked at you. He'll be there for sure.

870
01:03:21,600 --> 01:03:22,920
I hope so.

871
01:03:23,120 --> 01:03:26,520
What do you think, Josephine?
What does your crystal ball say?

872
01:03:27,200 --> 01:03:30,120
Sugar. Is Sugar in here?

873
01:03:30,200 --> 01:03:34,200
Sugar, you got the key? I'm locked out
and I'm makin' a puddle in the hall.

874
01:03:34,320 --> 01:03:36,720
See you on the bandstand, girls.

875
01:03:40,320 --> 01:03:43,800
What are you tryin' to do to that girl,
puttin' on a millionaire act?

876
01:03:44,000 --> 01:03:47,920
And that phoney accent?
Nobody talks like that.

877
01:03:48,000 --> 01:03:50,120
I've seen you pull
some low tricks on women.

878
01:03:50,200 --> 01:03:53,920
This is without doubt
the trickiest, lowest, meanest...

879
01:03:59,720 --> 01:04:01,920
I'm not afraid of you.

880
01:04:03,600 --> 01:04:05,400
I'm thin, but I'm wiry.

881
01:04:05,600 --> 01:04:09,400
You're gonna get hurt.
When I'm aroused, I'm a tiger.

882
01:04:09,600 --> 01:04:14,120
Joe. Don't look at me like that.
It was all a joke. I didn't mean any harm.

883
01:04:14,200 --> 01:04:17,240
I'm gonna press
the suit myself. Telephone.

884
01:04:17,440 --> 01:04:19,640
Answer the tele...phone.

885
01:04:23,840 --> 01:04:25,360
Hello?

886
01:04:26,560 --> 01:04:28,640
Yes, this is 413.

887
01:04:28,840 --> 01:04:32,160
Ship to shore? All right, I'll take it.

888
01:04:32,240 --> 01:04:34,840
Daphne? It's that naughty boy again.

889
01:04:34,960 --> 01:04:37,160
You know - Osgood? In the elevator?

890
01:04:37,240 --> 01:04:39,840
You slapped my face?

891
01:04:41,040 --> 01:04:43,640
- Who is this?
- This is her roommate.

892
01:04:43,840 --> 01:04:45,960
Daphne can't talk right now. Is it urgent?

893
01:04:46,040 --> 01:04:48,560
Well, it is to me.
Will you give her a message?

894
01:04:48,640 --> 01:04:52,840
Tell her I'd like her to have supper with
me on my yacht after the show tonight.

895
01:04:53,040 --> 01:04:56,040
Got it. Supper, yacht,
after the show. I'll tell her.

896
01:04:56,160 --> 01:04:59,640
- Your yacht?
- The New Caledonia. That's its name.

897
01:04:59,760 --> 01:05:04,160
The Old Caledonia went down
during a wild party off Cape Hatteras.

898
01:05:04,360 --> 01:05:09,240
But tell her not to worry. This'll be a quiet
little midnight snack, just the two of us.

899
01:05:10,640 --> 01:05:14,160
Just the two of you?
What about the crew?

900
01:05:14,240 --> 01:05:18,160
That's all been taken care of.
I'm giving them shore leave.

901
01:05:18,360 --> 01:05:20,640
We'll have cold pheasant
with champagne.

902
01:05:20,840 --> 01:05:25,240
I've checked with the coastguard.
There's gonna be a full moon tonight.

903
01:05:25,440 --> 01:05:29,560
And tell her I've got
a new batch of Rudy Vallee records.

904
01:05:30,840 --> 01:05:34,360
That's good thinking.
Daphne's a pushover for him.

905
01:05:34,440 --> 01:05:36,840
Pushover for who? What...

906
01:05:36,960 --> 01:05:38,960
Yes, Mr Fielding.

907
01:05:39,160 --> 01:05:42,760
You'll pick her up after the show
in your motorboat. Goodbye.

908
01:05:42,840 --> 01:05:44,640
What's that you said?

909
01:05:44,760 --> 01:05:49,160
- "Zowie." I'll give her the message.
- What message? What motorboat?

910
01:05:49,240 --> 01:05:53,240
You got it made. Fielding wants to have
cold pheasant with you on his yacht.

911
01:05:53,440 --> 01:05:56,960
Just the three of you on that
great big boat. You, him and Rudy Vallee.

912
01:05:57,040 --> 01:05:59,360
Fat chance. Call him back
and say I'm not goin'.

913
01:05:59,560 --> 01:06:01,160
Of course you're not.

914
01:06:01,240 --> 01:06:03,160
I'm going.

915
01:06:03,840 --> 01:06:06,640
You're gonna be on the boat
with that dirty old man?

916
01:06:06,760 --> 01:06:08,840
I'm gonna be on the boat with Sugar.

917
01:06:09,040 --> 01:06:11,760
- Where's he gonna be?
- He's gonna be ashore with you.

918
01:06:11,840 --> 01:06:13,440
- With me?
- That's right.

919
01:06:13,640 --> 01:06:16,360
Oh, no. Not tonight, Josephine.

920
01:07:28,440 --> 01:07:31,440
Daphne, your boyfriend's waving at you.

921
01:07:31,640 --> 01:07:33,520
You can both go take a flyin' jump.

922
01:07:33,720 --> 01:07:36,640
Remember, he's your date
for tonight, so smile.

923
01:07:38,120 --> 01:07:42,440
Oh, you can do better than that.
Give him the teeth, the whole personality.

924
01:07:51,920 --> 01:07:54,440
Why do I let you talk me
into these things? Why?

925
01:07:54,640 --> 01:07:57,240
Because we're pals. The two musketeers.

926
01:07:57,320 --> 01:08:01,040
Don't give me the musketeers.
How am I gonna keep him ashore?

927
01:08:01,120 --> 01:08:03,920
Tell him you get seasick.
Play miniature golf with him.

928
01:08:04,120 --> 01:08:08,240
Oh, no. I'm not gonna get caught
in a miniature sand trap with that guy.

929
01:08:12,720 --> 01:08:15,040
Hi. Which of you dolls is Daphne?

930
01:08:15,120 --> 01:08:16,720
Bull fiddle.

931
01:08:16,840 --> 01:08:19,040
From satchel mouth at table seven.

932
01:08:23,920 --> 01:08:27,440
- This is from me to you, doll.
- Beat it, buster.

933
01:08:27,640 --> 01:08:31,040
Never mind leaving your door open.
I got a passkey.

934
01:08:36,520 --> 01:08:40,440
- What are you doin' with my flowers?
- Borrowing 'em. You'll get 'em back.

935
01:09:08,920 --> 01:09:12,040
I guess he's not gonna show up.
It's five minutes to one.

936
01:09:12,120 --> 01:09:15,720
- Do you suppose he forgot?
- You know how those millionaires are.

937
01:09:15,920 --> 01:09:17,640
These came for you.

938
01:09:17,840 --> 01:09:19,520
For me?

939
01:09:21,120 --> 01:09:22,440
It's Shell Oil.

940
01:09:22,640 --> 01:09:24,640
- No!
- Yes!

941
01:09:24,720 --> 01:09:26,840
He wants to have supper
with me on his yacht.

942
01:09:27,040 --> 01:09:28,640
He's picking me up at the pier.

943
01:09:28,840 --> 01:09:30,120
- No!
- Yes.

944
01:09:30,320 --> 01:09:32,040
You heard her - yes.

945
01:09:32,120 --> 01:09:36,440
Josephine, just imagine. Me,
Sugar Kowalczyk from Sandusky, Ohio,

946
01:09:36,640 --> 01:09:38,320
on a millionaire's yacht.

947
01:09:38,520 --> 01:09:41,040
If my mother could only see me now.

948
01:09:43,120 --> 01:09:45,520
I hope my mother never finds out.

949
01:09:46,920 --> 01:09:50,120
That's it for tonight.
This is Sweet Sue saying good night,

950
01:09:50,240 --> 01:09:55,440
reminding all you daddies out there
that every girl in my band is a virtuoso.

951
01:09:55,640 --> 01:09:58,120
And I intend to keep it that way.

952
01:10:04,120 --> 01:10:06,120
- Good luck.
- Thanks.

953
01:11:32,480 --> 01:11:35,280
But it's such a waste.
A full moon, an empty yacht.

954
01:11:35,360 --> 01:11:37,680
- I'll throw up.
- Then let's go dancing.

955
01:11:37,760 --> 01:11:40,080
There's a roadhouse down the coast...

956
01:11:44,160 --> 01:11:47,080
Well, I'll be.... He does have a bicycle.

957
01:11:47,160 --> 01:11:49,080
Who?

958
01:11:49,160 --> 01:11:51,080
About the roadhouse?

959
01:11:51,160 --> 01:11:53,360
They have a Cuban band
that's the berries.

960
01:11:53,480 --> 01:11:57,360
Let's go there, blindfold the orchestra
and tango till dawn.

961
01:11:57,480 --> 01:11:59,480
- You know something, Mr Fielding?
- What?

962
01:11:59,560 --> 01:12:01,480
You're dynamite.

963
01:12:01,680 --> 01:12:04,360
You're a pretty hot
little firecracker yourself.

964
01:12:54,760 --> 01:12:56,880
Ahoy, there.

965
01:12:57,960 --> 01:13:00,080
Ahoy.

966
01:13:07,880 --> 01:13:10,280
- Been waiting long?
- It's not how long you wait.

967
01:13:10,360 --> 01:13:14,160
- It's who you're waiting for.
- Thank you. And for the flowers.

968
01:13:14,280 --> 01:13:18,880
I wanted them to fly orchids from our
greenhouse, but Long Island is fogged in.

969
01:13:19,080 --> 01:13:20,960
It's the thought that counts.

970
01:13:27,880 --> 01:13:29,760
I seem to be out of gas.

971
01:13:29,880 --> 01:13:33,680
It's sort of funny, you being out of gas.
I mean, Shell Oil and everyzhing.

972
01:13:33,880 --> 01:13:35,880
Oops. There.

973
01:13:40,680 --> 01:13:42,800
It seems to be stuck in reverse.

974
01:13:44,200 --> 01:13:47,600
I just got this motorboat.
It's an an experimental model.

975
01:13:47,720 --> 01:13:49,800
It seems like they're on the wrong track.

976
01:13:49,920 --> 01:13:52,520
Do you mind riding backwards?
It may take a little longer.

977
01:13:52,720 --> 01:13:55,920
It's not how long it takes.
It's who's taking you.

978
01:14:21,120 --> 01:14:23,120
It looked so small from the beach.

979
01:14:23,200 --> 01:14:26,320
But when you're on it, it's like
a cruiser or a destroyer.

980
01:14:26,520 --> 01:14:31,120
It's just regulation-size. We have three.
Mother keeps hers in Southampton.

981
01:14:31,200 --> 01:14:34,320
Daddy's is in Venezuela.
The company is laying a new pipeline.

982
01:14:34,400 --> 01:14:38,200
My dad's more interested in railroads.
Baltimore and Ohio.

983
01:14:38,400 --> 01:14:40,520
Which is the port
and which is the starboard?

984
01:14:40,600 --> 01:14:43,320
That depends on
whether you're coming or going.

985
01:14:43,400 --> 01:14:47,320
I mean, normally the aft
is on the other side of the stern.

986
01:14:47,400 --> 01:14:51,920
And that's the bridge. So that you can get
from one side of the boat to the other.

987
01:14:52,000 --> 01:14:55,600
- Would you like a glass of champagne?
- Love it. Which way?

988
01:14:58,320 --> 01:15:02,120
- You have an upstairs and a downstairs.
- Yes, the hurricane cellar.

989
01:15:03,800 --> 01:15:08,120
And another nice thing about
this yacht - lots of closet space.

990
01:15:08,200 --> 01:15:12,400
Now, let me see. Where do you
suppose the steward set it up?

991
01:15:15,120 --> 01:15:17,000
In here.

992
01:15:18,400 --> 01:15:19,920
Of course. How silly of me.

993
01:15:20,000 --> 01:15:23,520
On Thursdays they always
serve me in the small salon.

994
01:15:31,600 --> 01:15:34,600
It's exquisite. Like a floating mansion.

995
01:15:34,720 --> 01:15:36,720
It's all right for a bachelor.

996
01:15:37,800 --> 01:15:41,320
- What a beautiful fish.
- I caught him off Cape Hatteras.

997
01:15:42,200 --> 01:15:44,200
What is it?

998
01:15:44,320 --> 01:15:47,120
It's a member of the herring family.

999
01:15:47,800 --> 01:15:49,720
A herring?

1000
01:15:49,920 --> 01:15:54,320
Isn't it amazing how they get those
big fish into those little glass jars?

1001
01:15:54,520 --> 01:15:56,600
They shrink when they're marinated.

1002
01:15:56,720 --> 01:15:58,720
- Champagne?
- I don't mind if I do.

1003
01:15:58,800 --> 01:16:01,400
Well, down the hatch, as we say at sea.

1004
01:16:01,520 --> 01:16:03,520
Bon voyage.

1005
01:16:07,400 --> 01:16:10,000
- Look at all that silverware.
- Trophies.

1006
01:16:10,200 --> 01:16:13,400
You know. Skeet shooting,
dog breeding, water polo.

1007
01:16:13,520 --> 01:16:15,520
Isn't water polo terribly dangerous?

1008
01:16:15,720 --> 01:16:18,120
I'll say. I had two ponies
drowned under me.

1009
01:16:18,320 --> 01:16:20,200
Where's your shell collection?

1010
01:16:20,400 --> 01:16:22,720
Yes, of course.
Where could they have put it?

1011
01:16:22,920 --> 01:16:25,400
You see, on Thursdays
I'm sort of lost around here.

1012
01:16:25,600 --> 01:16:28,400
- What's on Thursdays?
- It's the crew's night off.

1013
01:16:28,600 --> 01:16:31,720
- You mean we're alone on the boat?
- Completely.

1014
01:16:31,800 --> 01:16:35,400
I've never been completely alone
with a man in the middle of the night,

1015
01:16:35,600 --> 01:16:38,120
- in the middle of the ocean.
- Oh, it's perfectly safe.

1016
01:16:38,200 --> 01:16:41,000
We're anchored.
The ship's in shipshape shape.

1017
01:16:41,200 --> 01:16:43,720
The coastguard will call
if any icebergs appear.

1018
01:16:44,400 --> 01:16:45,720
It's not the icebergs.

1019
01:16:45,800 --> 01:16:49,000
But certain men would try to
take advantage of a situation like this.

1020
01:16:49,160 --> 01:16:52,840
- You're flattering me.
- Of course, I'm sure you're a gentleman.

1021
01:16:53,760 --> 01:16:57,360
It's not that. It's just that I'm harmless.

1022
01:16:57,440 --> 01:17:00,040
- Harmless? How?
- I don't know how to put it,

1023
01:17:00,240 --> 01:17:02,360
but I've got this thing about girls.

1024
01:17:02,440 --> 01:17:05,840
- What thing?
- They just sort of leave me cold.

1025
01:17:06,040 --> 01:17:07,760
You mean, like, frigid?

1026
01:17:07,960 --> 01:17:10,240
Well, it's more like a mental block.

1027
01:17:10,440 --> 01:17:13,760
When I'm with a girl,
it does absolutely nothing to me.

1028
01:17:13,840 --> 01:17:18,160
- Have you tried?
- Have I. I'm trying all the time.

1029
01:17:24,440 --> 01:17:27,240
See? Nothing.

1030
01:17:27,360 --> 01:17:29,840
- Nothing at all?
- Complete washout.

1031
01:17:29,960 --> 01:17:33,040
- That makes me feel just awful.
- My dear, it's not your fault.

1032
01:17:33,240 --> 01:17:36,040
Now and then Mother Nature
throws somebody a dirty curve.

1033
01:17:36,160 --> 01:17:38,160
Something goes wrong inside.

1034
01:17:38,240 --> 01:17:41,160
- You mean you can't fall in love?
- Not any more.

1035
01:17:41,360 --> 01:17:43,960
I was in love once,
but I'd rather not talk about it.

1036
01:17:44,160 --> 01:17:46,960
- Would you like a little cold pheasant?
- What happened?

1037
01:17:47,160 --> 01:17:50,240
- I don't want to bore you.
- You couldn't possibly.

1038
01:17:50,440 --> 01:17:52,360
Well...

1039
01:17:52,440 --> 01:17:54,560
It was my freshman year at Princeton.

1040
01:17:54,760 --> 01:17:56,960
There was this girl. Her name was Nellie.

1041
01:17:57,040 --> 01:17:59,640
Her father was
the vice president of Hupmobile.

1042
01:17:59,840 --> 01:18:02,160
She wore glasses, too.

1043
01:18:02,360 --> 01:18:04,760
That summer we were
at the Grand Canyon.

1044
01:18:04,840 --> 01:18:07,640
We were on the highest ledge
watching the sunset,

1045
01:18:07,760 --> 01:18:10,160
when suddenly we got
this impulse to kiss.

1046
01:18:10,240 --> 01:18:13,560
I took off my glasses.
She took off her glasses.

1047
01:18:13,640 --> 01:18:15,640
I took a step toward her.

1048
01:18:15,840 --> 01:18:18,640
She took a step toward me.

1049
01:18:19,240 --> 01:18:22,960
Yes. Eight hours later
they brought her up by mule.

1050
01:18:23,040 --> 01:18:26,960
I gave her three transfusions.
We had the same type blood - type O.

1051
01:18:27,040 --> 01:18:29,840
But it was too late.

1052
01:18:29,960 --> 01:18:31,760
Talk about sad.

1053
01:18:31,840 --> 01:18:33,840
Ever since then,

1054
01:18:33,960 --> 01:18:37,360
numb, no feelings, like my heart
was shot full of Novocain.

1055
01:18:37,560 --> 01:18:39,760
You poor, poor boy.

1056
01:18:39,840 --> 01:18:42,640
Yes. All the money in the world,
and what good is it?

1057
01:18:42,760 --> 01:18:44,560
Mint sauce or cranberries?

1058
01:18:45,240 --> 01:18:48,240
How can you think about food
at a time like this?

1059
01:18:48,360 --> 01:18:50,360
What else is there for me?

1060
01:18:50,440 --> 01:18:53,960
- Is it that hopeless?
- My family did everyzhing they could.

1061
01:18:54,040 --> 01:18:56,640
Hired the most beautiful
French upstairs maids.

1062
01:18:56,840 --> 01:18:59,840
Got a special tutor to read me
books that were banned in Boston.

1063
01:18:59,960 --> 01:19:02,040
Imported a troupe of Balinese dancers

1064
01:19:02,240 --> 01:19:05,360
with those bells on their ankles
and long fingernails.

1065
01:19:05,560 --> 01:19:07,760
What a waste of money.

1066
01:19:07,840 --> 01:19:10,160
Have you ever tried American girls?

1067
01:19:10,240 --> 01:19:11,960
Why?

1068
01:19:17,440 --> 01:19:19,440
Was that anyzhing?

1069
01:19:20,440 --> 01:19:22,440
Thanks just the same.

1070
01:19:23,160 --> 01:19:25,360
You should see a doctor - a good doctor.

1071
01:19:25,440 --> 01:19:29,960
I have. I spent six months in Vienna
with Professor Freud, flat on my back.

1072
01:19:31,040 --> 01:19:35,560
Then there were the Mayo brothers,
injections, hypnosis, mineral baths.

1073
01:19:35,640 --> 01:19:38,040
If I wasn't such a coward, I'd kill myself.

1074
01:19:39,440 --> 01:19:41,360
Don't say that.

1075
01:19:41,560 --> 01:19:44,160
There must be some girl
someplace that could...

1076
01:19:44,240 --> 01:19:48,360
If I ever found a girl that could,
I'd marry her just like that.

1077
01:19:49,240 --> 01:19:52,040
- Would you do me a favour?
- Certainly. What is it?

1078
01:19:52,160 --> 01:19:55,960
I may not be Dr Freud or a Mayo brother
or one of those French upstairs girls,

1079
01:19:56,080 --> 01:19:58,680
but could I take another crack at it?

1080
01:19:59,480 --> 01:20:01,880
All right, if you insist.

1081
01:20:14,280 --> 01:20:18,280
- Anyzhing this time?
- I'm afraid not.

1082
01:20:18,480 --> 01:20:21,680
- Terribly sorry.
- Would you like some more champagne?

1083
01:20:24,080 --> 01:20:27,680
Maybe if we had some music.
How do you dim these lights?

1084
01:20:28,800 --> 01:20:32,280
Look, it's terribly sweet of you
to want to help out, but it's no use.

1085
01:20:32,480 --> 01:20:34,600
I think the light switch is over there.

1086
01:20:40,080 --> 01:20:42,080
That's the radio.

1087
01:20:42,200 --> 01:20:45,600
It's like taking someone
to a concert when he's tone-deaf.

1088
01:21:20,280 --> 01:21:22,800
You're not giving yourself a chance.

1089
01:21:22,880 --> 01:21:25,600
Don't fight it.

1090
01:21:26,080 --> 01:21:28,080
Relax.

1091
01:21:40,880 --> 01:21:43,000
It's like smoking without inhaling.

1092
01:21:43,200 --> 01:21:45,080
So inhale.

1093
01:22:07,280 --> 01:22:08,600
Daphne,

1094
01:22:08,680 --> 01:22:11,000
- you're leading again.
- Sorry.

1095
01:22:24,680 --> 01:22:26,200
Well?

1096
01:22:27,680 --> 01:22:29,680
I'm not quite sure.

1097
01:22:29,800 --> 01:22:32,080
Would you try it again?

1098
01:22:41,880 --> 01:22:45,000
I got a funny sensation in my toes.

1099
01:22:45,880 --> 01:22:48,880
Like someone was barbecuing them
over a slow flame.

1100
01:22:50,280 --> 01:22:52,880
Let's throw another log on the fire.

1101
01:23:02,080 --> 01:23:04,640
I think you're on the right track.

1102
01:23:05,280 --> 01:23:08,720
I must be. Your glasses
are beginning to steam up.

1103
01:23:32,440 --> 01:23:34,840
I never knew it could be like this.

1104
01:23:36,240 --> 01:23:38,120
Thank you.

1105
01:23:38,320 --> 01:23:41,320
They told me I was kaput,
finished, all washed up.

1106
01:23:41,440 --> 01:23:45,040
And here you are, making a chump
out of all those experts.

1107
01:23:47,520 --> 01:23:49,840
Mineral baths. Now, really.

1108
01:23:49,920 --> 01:23:53,240
Where did you learn to kiss like that?

1109
01:23:53,320 --> 01:23:56,520
I used to sell kisses for the Milk Fund.

1110
01:24:05,920 --> 01:24:10,720
Tomorrow, remind me to send
a cheque for $100,000 to the Milk Fund.

1111
01:25:13,320 --> 01:25:14,720
Whoops.

1112
01:25:41,440 --> 01:25:44,320
- Good night.
- Good morning.

1113
01:25:44,440 --> 01:25:46,440
How much do I owe the Milk Fund so far?

1114
01:25:46,640 --> 01:25:49,040
$850,000.

1115
01:25:49,240 --> 01:25:51,720
Let's make it an even million.

1116
01:26:11,520 --> 01:26:14,160
I forgot to give you a receipt.

1117
01:26:53,760 --> 01:26:55,960
Hi, Jerry. Everyzhing under control?

1118
01:26:56,080 --> 01:26:58,680
Have I got things to tell you.

1119
01:26:58,760 --> 01:27:02,080
- What happened?
- I'm engaged.

1120
01:27:02,160 --> 01:27:05,480
Congratulations. Who's the lucky girl?

1121
01:27:05,560 --> 01:27:07,160
I am.

1122
01:27:11,280 --> 01:27:12,960
What?

1123
01:27:13,080 --> 01:27:16,280
Osgood proposed to me.
We're planning a June wedding.

1124
01:27:18,680 --> 01:27:21,560
What are you talking about?
You can't marry Osgood.

1125
01:27:22,680 --> 01:27:26,280
- Do you think he's too old for me?
- Jerry, you can't be serious.

1126
01:27:26,360 --> 01:27:28,960
Why not? He keeps
marryin' girls all the time.

1127
01:27:30,360 --> 01:27:32,480
But... you're not a girl. You're a guy.

1128
01:27:32,560 --> 01:27:34,480
And why would a guy
wanna marry a guy?

1129
01:27:34,680 --> 01:27:36,480
Security.

1130
01:27:37,560 --> 01:27:40,880
- Jerry, lie down. You're not well.
- Stop treatin' me like a child.

1131
01:27:40,960 --> 01:27:44,080
- I'm not stupid. I know there's a problem.
- I'll say there is.

1132
01:27:44,280 --> 01:27:48,680
His mother. We need her approval. But
I'm not worried because I don't smoke.

1133
01:27:51,480 --> 01:27:54,880
- Jerry, there's another problem.
- Like what?

1134
01:27:54,960 --> 01:27:58,760
- Like your honeymoon.
- We've been discussing that.

1135
01:27:58,960 --> 01:28:02,880
He wants to go to the Riviera,
but I kinda lean towards Niagara Falls.

1136
01:28:06,360 --> 01:28:09,480
Jerry, you're outta your mind.
You can't get away with this.

1137
01:28:09,680 --> 01:28:13,360
I don't expect it to last.
I'll tell him the truth when the time comes.

1138
01:28:13,480 --> 01:28:16,080
- Like when?
- Like right after the ceremony.

1139
01:28:16,280 --> 01:28:19,480
Then we get a quick annulment,
he makes a nice settlement on me

1140
01:28:19,680 --> 01:28:22,680
and I keep gettin' those
alimony cheques every month.

1141
01:28:26,880 --> 01:28:28,880
Jerry, listen to me.

1142
01:28:28,960 --> 01:28:32,160
There are laws, conventions.
It's just not been done.

1143
01:28:32,880 --> 01:28:35,880
Joe, this may be my last chance
to marry a millionaire.

1144
01:28:35,960 --> 01:28:39,880
Jerry, will you take my advice?
Forget about the whole thing, will you?

1145
01:28:39,960 --> 01:28:43,680
Just keep telling yourself you're a boy.

1146
01:28:43,760 --> 01:28:46,880
- I'm a boy.
- That's the boy.

1147
01:28:46,960 --> 01:28:50,280
I'm a boy, I'm a boy, I'm a...

1148
01:28:50,480 --> 01:28:54,080
I wish I were dead.
I'm a boy. Boy, oh boy, am I a boy.

1149
01:28:54,160 --> 01:28:56,480
What about my engagement present?

1150
01:28:56,560 --> 01:28:59,880
- What engagement present?
- Osgood gave me a bracelet.

1151
01:29:01,560 --> 01:29:03,160
Hey, these are real diamonds.

1152
01:29:03,280 --> 01:29:05,880
Of course they're real.
You think my fianc? is a bum?

1153
01:29:05,960 --> 01:29:10,360
- I guess I'll have to give it back to him.
- Wait a minute, Jerry. Let's not be hasty.

1154
01:29:10,480 --> 01:29:13,880
After all, we don't wanna
hurt Osgood's feelings.

1155
01:29:16,760 --> 01:29:19,280
- Just a minute.
- It's me. Sugar.

1156
01:29:26,400 --> 01:29:27,200
Come in.

1157
01:29:28,400 --> 01:29:32,800
I thought I heard voices. I had to talk to
somebody. I don't feel like going to sleep.

1158
01:29:32,920 --> 01:29:36,600
- What you need is a slug of bourbon.
- Oh, no. I'm off that stuff for good.

1159
01:29:37,320 --> 01:29:40,720
- Did you have a nice time?
- Nice?

1160
01:29:40,800 --> 01:29:43,800
It was suicidally beautiful.

1161
01:29:44,000 --> 01:29:45,120
Did he get fresh?

1162
01:29:45,200 --> 01:29:48,520
Of course not. As a matter of fact,
it was just the other way around.

1163
01:29:48,720 --> 01:29:50,800
- You see, he needs help.
- What for?

1164
01:29:51,000 --> 01:29:53,600
Talk about elegant.
You should see the yacht.

1165
01:29:53,720 --> 01:29:57,120
Candlelight, mint sauce and cranberries.

1166
01:29:57,600 --> 01:29:59,800
Gee, I wish I'd been there.

1167
01:29:59,920 --> 01:30:02,200
I'm going to see him again
tonight - and every night.

1168
01:30:02,400 --> 01:30:04,120
I think he's going to propose.

1169
01:30:04,200 --> 01:30:06,920
- As soon as he gets up his nerve.
- That's some nerve.

1170
01:30:07,000 --> 01:30:09,120
Daphne got a proposal tonight.

1171
01:30:10,000 --> 01:30:12,200
- Really?
- From a rich millionaire.

1172
01:30:12,400 --> 01:30:14,120
That's wonderful.

1173
01:30:14,320 --> 01:30:16,400
- Poor Josephine.
- Me?

1174
01:30:16,520 --> 01:30:18,200
Well, Daphne has a beau, I have a beau...

1175
01:30:18,400 --> 01:30:20,920
If we could only find somebody for you.

1176
01:30:23,200 --> 01:30:25,120
Here I am, doll.

1177
01:30:50,400 --> 01:30:53,600
"Friends of Italian Opera" - that's us.

1178
01:30:53,720 --> 01:30:55,920
Register over there.

1179
01:31:04,320 --> 01:31:07,720
Spats Colombo. Delegate from Chicago.
South Side Chapter.

1180
01:31:08,720 --> 01:31:10,720
Thanks.

1181
01:31:10,800 --> 01:31:12,320
Hiya, Spats.

1182
01:31:12,400 --> 01:31:15,400
- We was layin' 8-1 you wouldn't show.
- Why wouldn't I?

1183
01:31:15,520 --> 01:31:18,520
We thought you was all broken up
about Toothpick Charlie.

1184
01:31:18,720 --> 01:31:22,800
- We all gotta go sometime.
- Yeah. You never know who's next.

1185
01:31:23,000 --> 01:31:25,200
OK, Spats. Report to the sergeant at arms.

1186
01:31:25,320 --> 01:31:28,920
- What for?
- Orders from Little Bonaparte.

1187
01:31:33,320 --> 01:31:36,120
- All right, Spats, get your hands up.
- What's the idea?

1188
01:31:36,320 --> 01:31:39,120
Little Bonaparte don't want
no hardware around.

1189
01:31:39,200 --> 01:31:41,320
All right, you're clean.

1190
01:31:41,520 --> 01:31:43,520
You're not.

1191
01:31:53,200 --> 01:31:55,600
It ain't loaded.

1192
01:32:03,200 --> 01:32:06,000
Next. What's in here?

1193
01:32:06,120 --> 01:32:09,400
My golf clubs. Putter, niblick, No.3 iron.

1194
01:32:10,400 --> 01:32:12,720
- What's this?
- My mashie.

1195
01:32:17,520 --> 01:32:19,920
See you at the banquet, Spats.

1196
01:32:20,800 --> 01:32:23,920
Where did you pick up that cheap trick?

1197
01:32:24,120 --> 01:32:26,400
Come on, boys.

1198
01:32:27,200 --> 01:32:29,360
Well. Spats Colombo, if I ever saw one.

1199
01:32:29,400 --> 01:32:31,640
Hello, copper.
What brings you to Florida?

1200
01:32:31,840 --> 01:32:33,760
I heard you opera-lovers were meetin'.

1201
01:32:33,960 --> 01:32:36,760
Thought I'd come in case
anybody decided to sing.

1202
01:32:36,840 --> 01:32:38,040
Big joke.

1203
01:32:38,160 --> 01:32:40,440
Where were you at 3pm
on St Valentine's Day?

1204
01:32:40,560 --> 01:32:43,440
- I was at Rigoletto.
- What's his first name and address?

1205
01:32:43,640 --> 01:32:45,560
It's an opera, you ignoramus.

1206
01:32:45,640 --> 01:32:48,840
- In the garage on Clark Street?
- Clark Street? Never heard of it.

1207
01:32:48,960 --> 01:32:52,360
Ever hear of Deluxe Cleaners
on Wabash Avenue?

1208
01:32:52,440 --> 01:32:55,560
The day after the shoot
you sent in spats with blood on 'em.

1209
01:32:55,640 --> 01:32:57,360
I cut myself while shaving.

1210
01:32:57,560 --> 01:33:00,160
- You shave with spats on?
- I sleep with my spats on.

1211
01:33:00,240 --> 01:33:03,560
Stop kidding. You vulcanised
Toothpick Charlie, and we know it.

1212
01:33:03,640 --> 01:33:04,840
You and who else?

1213
01:33:05,040 --> 01:33:08,760
Me and those two witnesses you
have been lookin' for all over Chicago.

1214
01:33:08,960 --> 01:33:11,640
Boys, know anyzhing about
any garage or witnesses?

1215
01:33:11,760 --> 01:33:14,360
Us? We was with you at Rigoletto's.

1216
01:33:14,440 --> 01:33:16,640
Honest.

1217
01:33:18,040 --> 01:33:22,160
Don't worry, Spats. One of these days
we're gonna dig up those two guys.

1218
01:33:22,360 --> 01:33:24,640
That's what you'll have to do - dig 'em up.

1219
01:33:33,960 --> 01:33:38,160
I feel like such a tramp, taking jewellery
from a man under false pretences.

1220
01:33:38,360 --> 01:33:41,840
Get it while you're young. Fix your lips
if you wanna look nice for Osgood.

1221
01:33:41,960 --> 01:33:44,440
It'll break his heart when
he finds out I can't marry him.

1222
01:33:44,640 --> 01:33:47,760
It'll break Sugar's heart when
she finds out I'm not a millionaire.

1223
01:33:47,840 --> 01:33:50,240
Can't make an omelette
without breakin' an egg.

1224
01:33:50,360 --> 01:33:52,560
- What's with the omelette?
- Nag, nag, nag.

1225
01:33:52,640 --> 01:33:57,240
We got a yacht, a bracelet, you've got
Osgood, I've got Sugar. We'll be cookin'.

1226
01:34:01,040 --> 01:34:03,040
- Joe!
- What?

1227
01:34:04,440 --> 01:34:07,960
Something tells me the omelette
is about to hit the fan.

1228
01:34:10,040 --> 01:34:12,040
Come on, Daphne.

1229
01:34:16,160 --> 01:34:18,040
- Going up.
- Hold it.

1230
01:34:25,760 --> 01:34:27,560
Three, please.

1231
01:34:38,360 --> 01:34:39,960
I don't mean to be forward,

1232
01:34:40,040 --> 01:34:43,040
but ain't I had the pleasure
of meetin' you two broads before?

1233
01:34:43,160 --> 01:34:45,640
- Oh, no.
- You must mean two other broads.

1234
01:34:45,840 --> 01:34:48,960
- You ever been in Chicago?
- Us?

1235
01:34:49,040 --> 01:34:51,360
We wouldn't be caught dead in Chicago.

1236
01:34:51,560 --> 01:34:52,760
Third floor.

1237
01:34:52,840 --> 01:34:55,840
- What floor are you on, sweetie?
- Never you mind.

1238
01:34:56,960 --> 01:34:58,840
Room 413. We'll be in touch.

1239
01:34:59,040 --> 01:35:01,640
Don't call us. We'll call you.

1240
01:35:13,440 --> 01:35:15,360
I tell you, Joe, they're onto us.

1241
01:35:15,560 --> 01:35:18,760
They're gonna line us up
against the wall and...

1242
01:35:18,840 --> 01:35:21,960
The cops will find two dead dames
and take us to the morgue

1243
01:35:22,040 --> 01:35:24,160
and when they undress us,
I'll die of shame.

1244
01:35:24,360 --> 01:35:27,240
- Shut up and keep packing.
- Yeah. OK, Joe.

1245
01:35:27,360 --> 01:35:29,440
- Not that, you idiot.
- They're from Osgood.

1246
01:35:29,560 --> 01:35:31,640
He wanted me to wear 'em tonight.

1247
01:35:35,240 --> 01:35:38,160
I tell you, I will never find
another man who's so good to me.

1248
01:35:38,400 --> 01:35:42,800
Joe, if we get outta this hotel alive,
we'll sell this bracelet, take the money,

1249
01:35:42,880 --> 01:35:45,880
grab a boat to South America
and hide out in a banana republic.

1250
01:35:46,080 --> 01:35:49,800
I figured if we eat nothing but bananas,
we could live there for 50 years.

1251
01:35:49,880 --> 01:35:51,680
If we get outta the hotel alive.

1252
01:35:51,800 --> 01:35:54,600
- Did we forget anyzhing?
- Yeah. The shaving stuff.

1253
01:35:54,680 --> 01:35:56,880
- And also Sugar.
- Sugar?

1254
01:35:57,080 --> 01:35:59,000
- Give me room 414.
- What are you doin'?

1255
01:35:59,080 --> 01:36:01,400
- Making a telephone call.
- Who has time?

1256
01:36:01,480 --> 01:36:03,600
We can't walk out on her
without a goodbye.

1257
01:36:03,800 --> 01:36:06,600
You usually walk out and leave 'em
with a kick in the teeth.

1258
01:36:06,680 --> 01:36:10,000
That's when I was a saxophone player.
Now I'm a millionaire.

1259
01:36:10,080 --> 01:36:13,400
Mail her a postcard.
Those gorillas may be here any minute.

1260
01:36:13,480 --> 01:36:16,080
Room 414?
This is the ship-to-shore operator.

1261
01:36:16,280 --> 01:36:17,800
Ship to shore?

1262
01:36:17,880 --> 01:36:20,200
Hey, Sugar, it's for you. From the yacht.

1263
01:36:25,000 --> 01:36:28,800
Hello, my dearest darling.
It's good to hear your voice.

1264
01:36:28,880 --> 01:36:31,200
I may throw up.

1265
01:36:32,680 --> 01:36:36,480
No, I didn't sleep too well, darling.
To tell the truth, I never closed an eye.

1266
01:36:36,680 --> 01:36:40,280
I never slept better.
I had the most wonderful dream.

1267
01:36:40,480 --> 01:36:42,680
I was still on the yacht
and the anchor broke loose.

1268
01:36:42,800 --> 01:36:45,400
We drifted for days and days.

1269
01:36:45,600 --> 01:36:47,280
You were the captain and I was the crew.

1270
01:36:47,400 --> 01:36:52,080
I kept a lookout for icebergs, I sorted
your shells and mixed your cocktails,

1271
01:36:52,200 --> 01:36:54,880
and I wiped the steam off your glasses.

1272
01:36:55,000 --> 01:36:58,800
And when I woke up, I wanted
to swim right back to you.

1273
01:36:59,600 --> 01:37:01,400
Yes...

1274
01:37:01,480 --> 01:37:03,680
Now, about our date for tonight...

1275
01:37:03,880 --> 01:37:06,600
I'll meet you on the pier again
right after the show.

1276
01:37:07,680 --> 01:37:10,600
I'm afraid not. I can't make it tonight.

1277
01:37:12,280 --> 01:37:14,800
Not tomorrow either. I have to leave.

1278
01:37:14,880 --> 01:37:18,480
Something unexpected came up.
I'm sailing right away.

1279
01:37:18,680 --> 01:37:20,680
Where to?

1280
01:37:20,880 --> 01:37:23,400
South America?

1281
01:37:24,080 --> 01:37:26,080
That is unexpected.

1282
01:37:26,880 --> 01:37:29,600
You see, we have
these oil interests in Venezuela.

1283
01:37:29,680 --> 01:37:33,600
I just got a cable from Dad. The board
of directors have decided on a merger.

1284
01:37:33,800 --> 01:37:36,600
A merger? How long will you be gone?

1285
01:37:38,680 --> 01:37:40,480
Quite a while.

1286
01:37:40,680 --> 01:37:43,480
As a matter of fact,
I'm not coming back at all.

1287
01:37:43,600 --> 01:37:45,600
You're not?

1288
01:37:46,000 --> 01:37:49,200
Well, it's all rather complicated.
What we call high finance.

1289
01:37:49,280 --> 01:37:53,880
It just so happens the president of the
Venezuelan oil syndicate has a daughter...

1290
01:37:54,000 --> 01:37:57,200
Oh. That kind of merger.

1291
01:37:57,280 --> 01:37:59,200
What is she like?

1292
01:37:59,280 --> 01:38:01,880
According to our tax adviser,
she's only so-so.

1293
01:38:02,080 --> 01:38:03,800
But that's the way the oil gushes.

1294
01:38:03,880 --> 01:38:07,400
A man in my position
has a responsibility to the stockholders.

1295
01:38:07,600 --> 01:38:11,000
All those little people
who have invested their life savings.

1296
01:38:11,080 --> 01:38:14,800
Of course. I understand.
At least, I think I do.

1297
01:38:14,880 --> 01:38:20,600
I knew you would. I only wish there
was something I could do for you.

1298
01:38:20,680 --> 01:38:24,080
But you have. You've given me
all that inside information.

1299
01:38:24,280 --> 01:38:26,080
Tomorrow I'm gonna call my broker

1300
01:38:26,200 --> 01:38:29,280
and have him buy me
50,000 shares of Venezuelan oil.

1301
01:38:29,480 --> 01:38:31,400
Smart move.

1302
01:38:31,600 --> 01:38:34,400
By the way, did you get my flowers?

1303
01:38:34,480 --> 01:38:36,800
You know, those orchids
from my greenhouse?

1304
01:38:37,000 --> 01:38:41,000
The fog finally lifted over Long Island
and they flew them down this morning.

1305
01:38:41,080 --> 01:38:44,680
That's strange. I sent 'em to your room.

1306
01:38:46,440 --> 01:38:48,640
They should have been delivered by now.

1307
01:38:52,240 --> 01:38:55,640
Hey, Dolores, will you see
if there's any flowers outside?

1308
01:39:01,320 --> 01:39:04,040
Yes, they're here. White orchids.

1309
01:39:04,120 --> 01:39:07,040
I haven't had white orchids
since I was a debutante.

1310
01:39:08,920 --> 01:39:10,840
What's this?

1311
01:39:11,920 --> 01:39:13,320
What's what?

1312
01:39:13,520 --> 01:39:16,040
Oh, that. Just a little going-away present.

1313
01:39:16,840 --> 01:39:19,640
Real diamonds.

1314
01:39:19,720 --> 01:39:24,040
They must be worth their weight in gold.
Are you always this generous?

1315
01:39:25,440 --> 01:39:26,840
Not always.

1316
01:39:27,040 --> 01:39:29,840
I wanted you to know how grateful
I am for what you did for me.

1317
01:39:29,920 --> 01:39:33,120
I didn't do anyzhing. It just happened.

1318
01:39:35,720 --> 01:39:38,440
The navigator just came in.
We're ready to cast off.

1319
01:39:38,640 --> 01:39:41,840
Well, anchors aweigh,
and have a bon voyage.

1320
01:39:41,920 --> 01:39:44,240
If you need an orchestra
to play at your wedding,

1321
01:39:44,440 --> 01:39:46,320
we'll be through here
in a couple of weeks.

1322
01:39:46,440 --> 01:39:48,840
Goodbye, my darling.

1323
01:39:48,920 --> 01:39:52,240
I don't know about the captain but
the navigator's gettin' his tail outta here.

1324
01:39:52,320 --> 01:39:55,440
- Yeah, let's shove off.
- Wait a minute. My bracelet.

1325
01:39:57,840 --> 01:39:59,520
What happened to my bracelet?

1326
01:39:59,640 --> 01:40:03,520
- Your bracelet? It's ours.
- All right. What happened to our bracelet?

1327
01:40:03,720 --> 01:40:07,840
- We did the right thing with it.
- You're not pullin' one of your old tricks.

1328
01:40:07,920 --> 01:40:10,240
No tricks, no mirrors,
nothing up my sleeve.

1329
01:40:10,320 --> 01:40:12,840
It's on the level this time.

1330
01:40:18,640 --> 01:40:20,640
Where's that bourbon?

1331
01:40:26,520 --> 01:40:30,920
- What's the matter, Sugar?
- I don't know. All of a sudden I'm thirsty.

1332
01:40:32,040 --> 01:40:33,840
How did you get that bracelet?

1333
01:40:33,920 --> 01:40:35,720
- You like it?
- I always did.

1334
01:40:35,920 --> 01:40:40,520
Junior gave it to me. He's gone
to South America to marry another girl.

1335
01:40:40,640 --> 01:40:43,640
- That's what you call high finance.
- That's what I call a louse.

1336
01:40:43,840 --> 01:40:47,240
If I were you, I'd take that bracelet
and throw it back in his face.

1337
01:40:47,320 --> 01:40:51,920
He's the first nice guy I've met in my life.
The only one that ever gave me anyzhing.

1338
01:40:52,040 --> 01:40:54,440
You'll forget him, Sugar.

1339
01:40:55,240 --> 01:41:00,040
How can I? No matter where I go, there'll
always be a Shell station on every corner.

1340
01:41:00,120 --> 01:41:03,320
I'll bring this back when it's empty.

1341
01:41:05,320 --> 01:41:08,520
Are you crazy? The place
is crawlin' with mobsters.

1342
01:41:08,720 --> 01:41:11,720
And you're makin' like
Diamond Jim Brady.

1343
01:41:11,920 --> 01:41:13,920
How are we gonna get outta here?
How are we gonna eat?

1344
01:41:14,040 --> 01:41:17,920
- We'll walk. If we have to, we'll starve.
- There's that "we" again.

1345
01:41:18,040 --> 01:41:21,240
Not that way. We don't wanna
run into Spats and his chums.

1346
01:41:29,920 --> 01:41:31,720
Your hands clean?

1347
01:41:31,840 --> 01:41:33,240
Over.

1348
01:41:33,320 --> 01:41:35,240
OK, button my spats.

1349
01:41:38,040 --> 01:41:40,040
You sure dress nice, boss.

1350
01:41:40,120 --> 01:41:43,120
Say, boss. I've been talking
with the other delegates.

1351
01:41:43,240 --> 01:41:47,440
The word is, Little Bonaparte is real sore
over what happened to Toothpick Charlie.

1352
01:41:47,520 --> 01:41:51,240
- Him and Charlie was choirboys together.
- Stop or I'll bust out cryin'.

1353
01:41:51,320 --> 01:41:54,880
He even got Charlie's last toothpick
from the garage. Had it gold-plated.

1354
01:41:55,080 --> 01:41:56,960
Like I was tellin' you fellas.

1355
01:41:57,160 --> 01:42:00,280
Little Bonaparte's gettin' soft.
Hasn't got it here any more.

1356
01:42:00,480 --> 01:42:02,680
Used to be like a rock.

1357
01:42:02,760 --> 01:42:07,360
- It's too bad. I think it's time he retired.
- Second the motion.

1358
01:42:07,480 --> 01:42:09,280
How are we gonna retire him?

1359
01:42:09,360 --> 01:42:11,360
Oh, we'll think of somethin' cute.

1360
01:42:11,560 --> 01:42:15,480
Little Bonaparte and Toothpick Charlie
will be singin' in the same choir again.

1361
01:42:18,560 --> 01:42:21,960
But this time we'll make sure
there are no witnesses.

1362
01:42:24,360 --> 01:42:28,080
Look. The two broads from the elevator.

1363
01:42:30,560 --> 01:42:33,080
Hey. Join us.

1364
01:42:33,680 --> 01:42:36,480
What's the matter with those dames?

1365
01:42:36,560 --> 01:42:38,760
Maybe those dames ain't dames.

1366
01:42:41,360 --> 01:42:43,960
Same faces, same instruments.

1367
01:42:47,560 --> 01:42:50,960
- Here's your Valentine's card.
- The two musicians from the garage.

1368
01:42:51,080 --> 01:42:55,760
They wouldn't be caught dead in Chicago,
so we'll finish the job here. Come on.

1369
01:43:13,480 --> 01:43:17,880
- All right, so what do we do now?
- First we gotta get out of these clothes.

1370
01:44:52,680 --> 01:44:53,680
What happened?

1371
01:44:53,880 --> 01:44:57,080
Me and Tiny had them cornered,
but we lost them in the shuffle.

1372
01:44:57,280 --> 01:45:00,360
- Where were you guys?
- We was with you, at Rigoletto's.

1373
01:45:00,480 --> 01:45:04,000
- Why, you stupid idiot.
- Boss, we'll get 'em after the banquet.

1374
01:45:04,120 --> 01:45:06,520
They can't be too far away.

1375
01:45:24,800 --> 01:45:26,800
Thank you.

1376
01:45:26,920 --> 01:45:29,120
Thank you, fellow opera-lovers.

1377
01:45:30,400 --> 01:45:34,320
It's been ten years since I elected myself
president of this organisation,

1378
01:45:34,400 --> 01:45:38,320
and, if I say so myself,
you made the right choice.

1379
01:45:40,000 --> 01:45:43,600
Let's look at the record.
In the last fiscal year,

1380
01:45:43,720 --> 01:45:47,720
we made $112 million before taxes.

1381
01:45:47,800 --> 01:45:50,720
Only we ain't payin' no taxes.

1382
01:45:51,800 --> 01:45:56,000
Of course, like in every business,
we had our little misunderstandings.

1383
01:45:57,800 --> 01:45:59,920
Let us now observe one minute of silence

1384
01:46:00,120 --> 01:46:04,320
in memory of seven of our members
from Chicago, North Side Chapter,

1385
01:46:04,400 --> 01:46:08,920
who are unable to be with us tonight
on account of bein' rubbed out.

1386
01:46:13,200 --> 01:46:15,200
You too, Spats.

1387
01:46:15,400 --> 01:46:17,320
Up.

1388
01:46:26,520 --> 01:46:28,120
Easy, now.

1389
01:46:28,320 --> 01:46:31,400
- You know when you come out?
- Yeah. Second time they sing:

1390
01:46:31,600 --> 01:46:35,520
For he's a jolly good fellow
